[{"name":"unreal_inspector","config":{"command":"C:/Program Files/Epic Games/UE_5.7/Engine/Plugins/Marketplace/Aura/PortablePython/Windows/python.exe","args":["C:/Program Files/Epic Games/UE_5.7/Engine/Plugins/Marketplace/Aura/MCP/unreal_inspector.py"]},"status":"connected","toolInfo":[{"name":"get_unreal_context","description":"\n    Get the user's currently selected context in the unreal editor. It includes assets the user wants specific help on and other up to date information.\n\n    If this tool fails, call `get_headless_status` to check the connection state, and use `launch_unreal_project` to start Unreal if it's not running.","inputSchema":{"type":"object","properties":{"only_get_drag_dropped_objects":{"default":false,"title":"Only Get Drag Dropped Objects","type":"boolean"}},"title":"get_unreal_contextArguments"}},{"name":"get_unreal_output_logs","description":"Read matching lines from the Unreal Editor output log file.\n\n    The active log lives at <ProjectRoot>/Saved/Logs/<ProjectName>.log and is appended to\n    while the editor runs. Returns a paginated slice of the lines that match the optional\n    filters. Useful for diagnosing runtime errors, warnings, and gameplay behavior without\n    requiring the user to open the editor's Output Log panel.\n\n    Args:\n        log_categories: Optional list of Unreal log categories to filter by, e.g.\n            [\"LogTemp\", \"LogBlueprintUserMessages\", \"LogAura\"]. Matched case-insensitively\n            against the category prefix on each line. None or empty list = no category filter.\n        substring_filter: Optional substring (case-insensitive) that must appear in the line.\n            An empty string means no substring filter.\n        max_lines: Maximum number of matching lines to return. Default 10. Maximum 100.\n        direction: 'tail' (default) returns the latest matches; 'head' returns the earliest.\n        offset: How many matching lines to skip from the chosen end before returning the page.\n            Use offset=max_lines to step to the next page. Defaults to 0 (no skip). Negative\n            values are clamped to 0.\n\n    Returns:\n        Header line with `direction`, `offset`, `max_lines`, `count`, and `total_matches`,\n        followed by the matching lines. `total_matches` lets callers tell whether another\n        page is available (more pages exist while `offset + count < total_matches`).\n    ","inputSchema":{"type":"object","properties":{"log_categories":{"anyOf":[{"items":{"type":"string"},"type":"array"},{"type":"null"}],"default":null,"title":"Log Categories"},"substring_filter":{"default":"","title":"Substring Filter","type":"string"},"max_lines":{"default":10,"title":"Max Lines","type":"integer"},"direction":{"default":"tail","title":"Direction","type":"string"},"offset":{"default":0,"title":"Offset","type":"integer"}},"title":"get_unreal_output_logsArguments"}},{"name":"get_asset_meta","description":"\n    Get metadata for a given asset file.\n    Depending on the type of asset, this could provide information like the list of components, variables, functions, events, etc.\n    Use get_asset_structs if you need deeper struct layout data referenced by the asset\n    This tool may also suggest other tool calls that can be used on the asset to get more detailed info.\n    **NEVER USE THIS TO SEARCH FOR '.h', and '.cpp' files.**\n    asset_path should be an asset soft path\n    e.g. don't use: Content/MyFolder/MyBlueprint.uasset\n    use: /Game/MyFolder/MyBlueprint.MyBlueprint\n\n    parts list should be a list of one or more strings choosing from the following values:\n    - PropertyDeclarations // Property/variable names and their types\n    - PropertyValues // Same as Properties but includes their values\n    - Events // Only for Blueprints\n    - Functions // Only for Blueprints\n    - Macros // Only for Blueprints\n    - Interfaces // Only for Blueprints\n    - Components // Only for Actor Blueprints\n    - MaterialParams // Only for Actor Blueprints (these are the material parameters of materials referenced by mesh components on an Actor BP)\n    - AnimGraphs // Only for AnimBPs\n    - WidgetTree // Only for UMG Widget BPs (to include widget property names/types you must also specify PropertyDeclarations. to include the values of the each property you must also specify PropertyValues)\n    You should try to request the minimal amount of parts for your task.\n    ","inputSchema":{"type":"object","properties":{"asset_path":{"title":"Asset Path","type":"string"},"parts":{"default":[],"items":{"type":"string"},"title":"Parts","type":"array"}},"required":["asset_path"],"title":"get_asset_metaArguments"}},{"name":"get_asset_structs","description":"\n    Get additional struct metadata used by the given asset file (typically a blueprint).\n    **NEVER USE THIS TO SEARCH FOR '.h', and '.cpp' files.**\n    asset_path should be an asset soft path\n    e.g. don't use: Content/MyFolder/MyBlueprint.uasset\n    use: /Game/MyFolder/MyBlueprint.MyBlueprint\n    ","inputSchema":{"type":"object","properties":{"asset_path":{"title":"Asset Path","type":"string"}},"required":["asset_path"],"title":"get_asset_structsArguments"}},{"name":"get_asset_graph","description":"\n    Get the detailed asset graph info for a given asset file.\n    You must provide the relative path from the project root to the asset file.\n    The strand_names parameter is an array containing names of functions, events, macros, or segments of the graph as listed in the output from get_asset_meta.\n    You should not leave strand_names empty. This tool may sometimes return more graph strands than you requested.\n    Use a soft path, instead of a relative file path.\n    e.g. don't use: Content/MyFolder/MyBlueprint.uasset\n    use: /Game/MyFolder/MyBlueprint.MyBlueprint\n\n    Don't reference the contents of the output directly in your responses, always refer to the nodes by their type or function name.\n    ","inputSchema":{"type":"object","properties":{"asset_path":{"title":"Asset Path","type":"string"},"strand_names":{"items":{"type":"string"},"title":"Strand Names","type":"array"}},"required":["asset_path","strand_names"],"title":"get_asset_graphArguments"}},{"name":"review_blueprint","description":"\n    Conduct an AI-powered code review of a blueprint and suggest improvements.\n\n    This tool analyzes the blueprint's graph structure and metadata, then uses an LLM\n    to provide expert feedback on performance, best practices, potential bugs, and code organization.\n\n    The review goes through a self-critique loop to ensure high-quality feedback.\n\n    You should print the output of the tool exactly with no summary or editorialization - except for any changes in language of the user\n\n    Args:\n        asset_path: The soft path to the blueprint file (e.g., /Game/MyFolder/MyBlueprint.MyBlueprint)\n        strand_names: Required array of function/event/macro names to review. Default to EventGraph.\n        previous_asset_path: Optional soft path to a previous version of the blueprint for changeset comparison.\n            When provided, the review will compare the changes between the previous and current versions.\n            Useful for reviewing diffs from source control or backup comparisons.\n        custom_instructions: Optional custom instructions from the user to guide the review (e.g., \"Focus on performance\", \"Ignore naming conventions\"). Never generate this unless the user provides them specifically.\n            Defaults to empty string.\n\n    Returns:\n        A detailed code review with suggestions for improvements.\n    ","inputSchema":{"type":"object","properties":{"asset_path":{"title":"Asset Path","type":"string"},"strand_names":{"default":["EventGraph"],"items":{"type":"string"},"title":"Strand Names","type":"array"},"previous_asset_path":{"default":"","title":"Previous Asset Path","type":"string"},"custom_instructions":{"default":"","title":"Custom Instructions","type":"string"}},"required":["asset_path"],"title":"review_blueprintArguments"}},{"name":"query_unreal_project_assets","description":"Query the unreal engine project to get shallow information using keywords. It returns relevant context from the user's project about assets, how they are related to each other, and shallow/medium file-info.\n    <IMPORTANT> When Searching CODE FILES ('.h' and '.cpp' files), return TWO FILES instead of ONE using num_files = 2 </IMPORTANT>,\n    FOR OTHER CASES, only return more than 1 file if you absolutely need to. Most answers will be in the top file.\n    Args:\n        query: The search query string\n        num_files: Number of files to return (default: 1, can be increased for more file results. Don't use unless you have to, and never use more than 3 if you must.)\n    ","inputSchema":{"type":"object","properties":{"query":{"title":"Query","type":"string"},"num_files":{"default":1,"title":"Num Files","type":"integer"}},"required":["query"],"title":"query_unreal_project_assetsArguments"}},{"name":"get_available_actors_in_level","description":"\n    Get a list of available actors in the specified `level` as an Unreal object path (defaults to current level if left unspecified) in hierarchical form and any associated information specified in flags.\n    The `get_flags` parameter can be used to specify what kind of actor info to return in the form \"Flag1|Flag2|Flag3|...\" where each flag is one of the following:\n    - `Label`: Include the Actor Label\n    - `FName`: Include the Actor FName\n    - `Class`: Include the Actor Class\n    - `Modifications`: Include the list of modified properties on the Actor (if any)\n    - `SpatialInfo`: Include the Actor Location/Rotation/Scale (if any)\n    Optional `filter_actor_class` parameter can be used to specify the actor base class name to filter results by. An empty string means no class filter.\n    Optional `filter_actor_label` parameter can be used to specify a full or partial actor name to filter results by. An empty string means no label filter.\n\n    If the level is using World Composition, it will only return actors from currently loaded sublevels.\n    If the level is using World Partition, it will only return actors from currently loaded partition cells.\n    ","inputSchema":{"type":"object","properties":{"level":{"title":"Level","type":"string"},"get_flags":{"title":"Get Flags","type":"string"},"filter_actor_class":{"title":"Filter Actor Class","type":"string"},"filter_actor_label":{"title":"Filter Actor Label","type":"string"}},"required":["level","get_flags","filter_actor_class","filter_actor_label"],"title":"get_available_actors_in_levelArguments"}},{"name":"fetch_python_best_practices","description":"Fetch core Python best practices for Unreal Engine scripting. Call this before delegating to python_agent or writing execute_unreal_python scripts. Returns guidance on property modification, asset registry, asset creation, levels, components, blueprints, subsystems, logging, and module imports.","inputSchema":{"type":"object","properties":{},"title":"fetch_python_best_practicesArguments"}},{"name":"fetch_gas_best_practices","description":"Fetch best practices for Unreal Engine Gameplay Ability System (GAS). Call this before proposing any GAS configuration or logic.","inputSchema":{"type":"object","properties":{},"title":"fetch_gas_best_practicesArguments"}},{"name":"fetch_ui_best_practices","description":"Fetch best practices for UMG (Unreal Motion Graphics) widget systems. Call this before providing any UMG/UI guidance or generating widget instructions.","inputSchema":{"type":"object","properties":{},"title":"fetch_ui_best_practicesArguments"}},{"name":"fetch_timeline_best_practices","description":"Fetch best practices for working with Timelines in Unreal Engine blueprints.\n    Call this BEFORE any task that involves time-based animations, doors, platforms, lights, or timelines.","inputSchema":{"type":"object","properties":{},"title":"fetch_timeline_best_practicesArguments"}},{"name":"fetch_curve_best_practices","description":"Fetch best practices for creating and editing standalone Curve assets (CurveFloat, CurveVector, CurveLinearColor).\n    Call this BEFORE any task that involves editing curve keyframes or importing curve data.","inputSchema":{"type":"object","properties":{},"title":"fetch_curve_best_practicesArguments"}},{"name":"fetch_performance_best_practices","description":"Fetch the canonical Unreal Engine profiling workflow.\n\n    Call this once at the start of a profiling task if you haven't already.\n    It teaches you HOW to use the profiler tools, interpret JSON output,\n    follow the process-of-elimination diagnostic steps, and (mandatory)\n    inspect spike frames via execute_unreal_python.\n\n    skill_name options:\n    - \"profiling_workflow\": the canonical workflow reference (only option).\n\n    Category-specific optimization skills (gpu_optimization, cpu_optimization,\n    memory_optimization) are intentionally NOT exposed here — they were\n    producing more noise than signal by encouraging generic best-practices\n    suggestions divorced from what the actual capture showed. Derive\n    per-category fixes directly from the data instead.\n    ","inputSchema":{"type":"object","properties":{"skill_name":{"default":"profiling_workflow","title":"Skill Name","type":"string"}},"title":"fetch_performance_best_practicesArguments"}},{"name":"fetch_eqs_best_practices","description":"Fetch best practices and API reference for working with EQS queries in Unreal Engine.\n    Call this BEFORE any task involving EQS, AI spatial reasoning, or environment queries.","inputSchema":{"type":"object","properties":{},"title":"fetch_eqs_best_practicesArguments"}},{"name":"import_PropertyModification_understanding","description":"Import understanding about PropertyModification in Unreal Python.","inputSchema":{"type":"object","properties":{},"title":"import_PropertyModification_understandingArguments"}},{"name":"import_FileSystem_understanding","description":"Import understanding about FileSystem in Unreal Python.","inputSchema":{"type":"object","properties":{},"title":"import_FileSystem_understandingArguments"}},{"name":"import_AssetRegistry_understanding","description":"Import understanding about AssetRegistry in Unreal Python.","inputSchema":{"type":"object","properties":{},"title":"import_AssetRegistry_understandingArguments"}},{"name":"import_AssetCreation_understanding","description":"Import understanding about AssetCreation in Unreal Python.","inputSchema":{"type":"object","properties":{},"title":"import_AssetCreation_understandingArguments"}},{"name":"import_AssetType_Level_understanding","description":"Import understanding about Level assets in Unreal Python.","inputSchema":{"type":"object","properties":{},"title":"import_AssetType_Level_understandingArguments"}},{"name":"import_AssetType_Blueprint_understanding","description":"Import understanding about Blueprint assets in Unreal Python.","inputSchema":{"type":"object","properties":{},"title":"import_AssetType_Blueprint_understandingArguments"}},{"name":"import_ActorComponentsAndSubobjects_understanding","description":"Import understanding about Actor Components and Actor subobjects in Unreal Python.","inputSchema":{"type":"object","properties":{},"title":"import_ActorComponentsAndSubobjects_understandingArguments"}},{"name":"import_AssetType_DataTable_understanding","description":"Import understanding about DataTable assets in Unreal Python.","inputSchema":{"type":"object","properties":{},"title":"import_AssetType_DataTable_understandingArguments"}},{"name":"import_AssetType_GameplayEffect_understanding","description":"Import understanding about GameplayEffect assets in Unreal Python.","inputSchema":{"type":"object","properties":{},"title":"import_AssetType_GameplayEffect_understandingArguments"}},{"name":"import_AssetType_UserWidget_understanding","description":"Import understanding about UserWidget assets in Unreal Python.","inputSchema":{"type":"object","properties":{},"title":"import_AssetType_UserWidget_understandingArguments"}},{"name":"import_AssetValidation_understanding","description":"Import understanding about AssetValidation in Unreal Python.","inputSchema":{"type":"object","properties":{},"title":"import_AssetValidation_understandingArguments"}},{"name":"import_Subsystems_understanding","description":"Import understanding about Subsystems in Unreal Python.","inputSchema":{"type":"object","properties":{},"title":"import_Subsystems_understandingArguments"}},{"name":"import_Color_understanding","description":"Import understanding about Color in Unreal Python.","inputSchema":{"type":"object","properties":{},"title":"import_Color_understandingArguments"}},{"name":"import_Logs_understanding","description":"Import understanding about Logs in Unreal Python.","inputSchema":{"type":"object","properties":{},"title":"import_Logs_understandingArguments"}},{"name":"import_AssetType_NiagaraSystem_understanding","description":"Import understanding about NiagaraSystem, NiagaraEmitter, and Niagara VFX assets in Unreal Python.","inputSchema":{"type":"object","properties":{},"title":"import_AssetType_NiagaraSystem_understandingArguments"}},{"name":"import_CurveAsset_understanding","description":"Import understanding about standalone Curve assets (CurveFloat, CurveVector, CurveLinearColor) in Unreal Python.","inputSchema":{"type":"object","properties":{},"title":"import_CurveAsset_understandingArguments"}},{"name":"import_IncludeOrImportModules_understanding","description":"Import understanding about the correct patterns for accessing functions from other Python scripts in Unreal Engine.","inputSchema":{"type":"object","properties":{},"title":"import_IncludeOrImportModules_understandingArguments"}},{"name":"fetch_understandings","description":"Fetch understanding knowledge for one or more categories in a single call. Call this ONCE with ALL categories you need.","inputSchema":{"type":"object","properties":{"categories":{"items":{"type":"string"},"title":"Categories","type":"array"}},"required":["categories"],"title":"fetch_understandingsArguments"}},{"name":"fetch_animation_skill","description":"Fetch animation skill reference for character replacement pipeline (hybrid C++ orchestration) or standalone forward alignment. Call this before generating animation/retarget Python scripts.","inputSchema":{"type":"object","properties":{"skill_name":{"title":"Skill Name","type":"string"}},"required":["skill_name"],"title":"fetch_animation_skillArguments"}},{"name":"fetch_level_design_skill","description":"Fetch level design skill reference for GeometryScript, blockout workflows, layout planning, validation, or exterior structures. Call this before generating level design scripts.","inputSchema":{"type":"object","properties":{"skill_name":{"title":"Skill Name","type":"string"}},"required":["skill_name"],"title":"fetch_level_design_skillArguments"}},{"name":"lock_plan_layer","description":"Validate and lock a planning artifact at a decomposition level. Call after generating a SitePlan (L0), BuildingShell (L1), or a single floor's zones (L2 layer). Returns validation results. Do NOT proceed to the next decomposition level until this returns status='locked'.","inputSchema":{"type":"object","properties":{"level":{"title":"Level","type":"string"},"data":{"title":"Data","type":"string"}},"required":["level","data"],"title":"lock_plan_layerArguments"}},{"name":"inspect_current_level","description":"Inspect the current level for precise information. Only use this for read-only actions. The python_agent tool can be used in cases where modifications are needed.\n    - First use get_asset_meta, query_unreal_project_assets and other tools to get relevant info (especially regarding gameplay functionality and specific classes and properties that are defined in other assets outside of the level).\n    - This tool can ONLY be used for inspecting current level contents. It cannot be used for anything else.\n\n   Rules:\n    - Must use logging to print the info that will help answer user request. Log output (including log type of each line) will be appended to the overall result. Minimize the total amount of output to only include necessary information.\n    - Must not modify the project - only use editor functions that are read-only in nature.\n    - When asking to filter results by some criteria, prefer implementing that criteria directly into your inspection logic.\n    - !!!IMPORTANT!!! If you require class/property names for it, you MUST use other MCP tools to gather their exact names.\n    - !!!IMPORTANT!!! When getting properties using get_editor_property, DO NOT use the snake_case name for the property.\n    Result will be of the form:\n        Success: bool\n        LOG OUTPUT: lines...\n    When Success == False it means the inspection failed for some reason. It will need to be corrected and reattempted.\n    This will automatically return runtime exception information when it fails, so there's no need for you to add exception handling unless it's helpful in implementing the inspection logic.\n    ","inputSchema":{"type":"object","properties":{"query_text":{"title":"Query Text","type":"string"},"python_script":{"title":"Python Script","type":"string"}},"required":["query_text","python_script"],"title":"inspect_current_levelArguments"}},{"name":"create_and_validate_blueprint_plan","description":"\n    Generate an implementation plan for a blueprint graph.\n\n    Used for PLANNING ONLY. Cannot be used to create or edit blueprints.\n\n    The plan is a structured JSON that describes the steps, variables, and custom events needed to implement the requested functionality.\n\n    !!!IMPORTANT!!!\n\n    ALWAYS call get_asset_meta tool on every relevant blueprint before calling this tool. DOUBLE CHECK FUNCTIONS, EVENTS, MACROS, AND COMPONENTS.\n    ALWAYS make sure the Blueprint file exists before calling this tool, and call create_assets FIRST if it does not.\n    !!!IMPORTANT!!!\n\n    1. Instructions should only be given for one graph at a time. Call this tool multiple times sequentially if you have multiple graphs to plan.\n    2. If you need to edit a material property, call get_blueprint_material_properties before this to get the material properties of the blueprint so you can say exactly what needs to be edited\n    3. Delay nodes can not be put into function graphs, they can only be put into event graphs.\n\n    Args:\n\n    specific_properties_to_change: A list of properties that this graph will change.\n        it should describe the entire path to the property and be AS SPECIFIC AS POSSIBLE.\n        It should be a list in the format: \"/Game/Path/To/MyClass.MyClass\" -> Component -> Property 1 -> SubProperty 3\" ....\n        This is highly relevant for materials, animations, and other properties\n        If you are changing materials, call get_blueprint_material_properties before this\n        to get the material properties of the blueprint so you can say exactly which material property needs to be edited.\n        For materials, this should ALWAYS end in a specific material property (e.g. BaseColor), not just the MaterialInstance.\n\n    user_prompt: Description of what this specific blueprint graph should do.\n        This is very important.\n        Always start with the Blueprint you plan to edit and the name of the graph you plan to edit or add like so\n        It is okay if a plan only has one step. Each step should be about 5 - 10 nodes max -- if a plan takes less than 5 nodes then it only has 1 step.\n        You must always submit user_prompt in the following format so that this tool can process it appropriately:\n        ```Blueprint:BlueprintName/Graph:GraphPage\n            //Step_Start 1\n              Plan Text\n            //Step_End\n            //Step_Start 2\n                Plan Text\n            //Step_End\n            //Step_Start..\n                ...\n            //Step_End\n            //Rest\n                Rest of the plan including summary and other context needs/properties to be included here.\n        ```\n        When generating the plan you should really:\n        Include any relevant details like other blueprints, functions, variables, interfaces etc... and how it should interact with them.\n        Include any relevant class references as well. Explain what the graph should do, how it should do it, and how it should interact with other variables/functions/etc...\n        make sure to call the get_blueprint_component_properties before hand to get a sense of the components and properties of any relevant blueprints\n        if the blueprint needs to change a property on a component, make sure to include which properties on which components need to change\n        if the blueprint needs to reference a specific class, include the class as well in the format: \"/Game/Path/To/MyClass.MyClass\"\n        At the end of the prompt, write a section called: RELEVANT_OTHER_BLUEPRINTS: which should include:\n            - a list of other classes relevant to this graph's generation (in the format: \"/Game/Path/To/MyClass.MyClass\")\n            - a list of components on other classes which are relevant to this graph's generation\n            - a list of properties on those components which are relevant to this graph's generation\n\n\n    blueprint_name: Name of the blueprint to edit (e.g., \"BP_MyActor\")\n    soft_path_from_project_root: Soft path to blueprint file (e.g., \"Game/MyFolder/BP_MyActor\")  You must provide the soft path from the project root to the blueprint file.\n    additional_blueprint_paths: Array of relevant Blueprint Assets (e.g. interfaces, other objects, things this BP interacts with) in a FULL soft paths from project root. (e.g., [\"Game/MyFolder/BP_RelevantActor\",\"Game/MyFolder/BP_RelevantMaterial\"])   You must provide the soft path from the project root to the blueprint file for each in the array--  do not use /Content !!\n    graph_page: Name of the graph to edit. For functions this is the name of the function, for EventGraphs this is the name of the UbergraphPage (ie \"EventGraph\" for the main event graph) NOT the name of a specific event. The results of get_asset_meta will indicate which functions should be implemented as events (if any).\n    graph_type: Type of graph to insert into. Must be one of the following:\n        \"EventGraph\", (used for Interface Events (interface functions without return values), Events, Custom Events, Parent Events / Custom Events Overrides)\n        \"Function\", (used for Custom Functions, Parent OverrideFunctions, Interface Functions (interface functions with return nodes. DO NOT use this for interface \"functions\" with no return nodes!!!), )\n        \"Macro\", (used for Macros)\n    only_change_part_of_graph: Whether this is only a partial edit to the graph (default: False). NOTE: Should typically be set to True when editing EventGraph\n\n    Returns:\n        JSON string containing the generated plan with steps, variables needed, custom events needed, and other planning information.\n    ","inputSchema":{"type":"object","properties":{"user_prompt":{"title":"User Prompt","type":"string"},"blueprint_name":{"title":"Blueprint Name","type":"string"},"soft_path_from_project_root":{"title":"Soft Path From Project Root","type":"string"},"specific_properties_to_change":{"default":[],"items":{"type":"string"},"title":"Specific Properties To Change","type":"array"},"only_change_part_of_graph":{"default":false,"title":"Only Change Part Of Graph","type":"boolean"},"additional_blueprint_paths":{"default":[],"items":{"type":"string"},"title":"Additional Blueprint Paths","type":"array"},"graph_page":{"default":"EventGraph","title":"Graph Page","type":"string"},"graph_type":{"default":"EventGraph","title":"Graph Type","type":"string"}},"required":["user_prompt","blueprint_name","soft_path_from_project_root"],"title":"create_and_validate_blueprint_planArguments"}},{"name":"get_code_examples","description":"Get code snippets of usage for a given set of keywords.\n    This tool will search Unreal Engine's code base.\n    This is useful for code validation.\n    If you know the full path to the file already and just want content directly from that file, use get_text_file_contents tool instead.\n\n    keywords: a list of keywords separated by \"|\". These should be specific terms like: \"GetActor\", etc...\n    time_limit: the maximum amount of time to spend searching for code examples.\n    include_engine_source: whether to include code examples from the engine source code.\n\n\n    Make sure you don't use generic keywords like \"C++\" or \"Implementation\" or \"example\", these will match to too many things in the code-base\n\n    The first time you run this tool, it will be slow and take a minute or two. <IMPORTANT>Make sure to let the user know that. Further uses will be fast.</IMPORTANT>\n    ","inputSchema":{"type":"object","properties":{"keywords":{"title":"Keywords","type":"string"},"time_limit":{"default":5,"title":"Time Limit","type":"number"},"include_engine_source":{"default":true,"title":"Include Engine Source","type":"boolean"}},"required":["keywords"],"title":"get_code_examplesArguments"}},{"name":"grep","description":"search tool based on ripgrep. Only use this when searching and reading code files.\n    *You must never use grep to understand overall project context, or with vague or broad search terms like \"\\.(uasset|umap)$\"*\n    Use this tool when you are searching for and editing CPP/Header files in the Unreal Project.\n\n    Usage:\n    - You should always try to use grep for exact symbol/string searches for *Code Files*.\n    - Whenever possible, use this instead of terminal grep/rg. This tool is faster and respects .gitignore/.cursorignore.\n    - Supports full regex syntax, e.g. \"log.*Error\", \"function\\s+\\w+\". Ensure you escape special chars to get exact matches, e.g. \"functionCall\\(\\\"\n    - Avoid overly broad glob patterns (e.g., '--glob *') as they bypass .gitignore rules and may be slow\n    - Only use 'type' (or 'glob' for file types) when certain of the file type needed.\n    - Output modes: \"content\" shows matching lines (default), \"files_with_matches\" shows only file paths, \"count\" shows match counts per file\n    - Pattern syntax: Uses ripgrep (not grep) - literal braces need escaping\n    - Multiline matching: By default patterns match within single lines only. For cross-line patterns, use multiline: true\n    - Results are capped for responsiveness; truncated results show \"at least\" counts.\n    - Use search_filenames=true to search for patterns in file names instead of file contents.\n\n    Args:\n        pattern: The regular expression pattern to search for in file contents (or file names if search_filenames=true)\n        path: File or directory to search in.\n        type: File type to search (rg --type). Common types: js, py, rust, go, java, etc.\n        glob: Glob pattern to filter files (e.g. \"*.js\", \"*.{ts,tsx}\").\n        output_mode: Output mode: \"content\", \"files_with_matches\", or \"count\"\n        A: Number of lines to show after each match\n        B: Number of lines to show before each match\n        C: Number of lines to show before and after each match\n        i: Case insensitive search. Defaults to false\n        multiline: Enable multiline mode where . matches newlines. Default: false.\n        head_limit: Limit output to first N lines/entries\n        search_filenames: Search file names instead of file contents. Default: false.\n        search_engine: Search engine files instead of game project files. Ignored if \"path\" is absolute. Default: false.\n    ","inputSchema":{"type":"object","properties":{"pattern":{"title":"Pattern","type":"string"},"path":{"anyOf":[{"type":"string"},{"type":"null"}],"default":null,"description":"File or directory to search in. Defaults to Cursor workspace roots.","title":"Path"},"type":{"anyOf":[{"type":"string"},{"type":"null"}],"default":null,"description":"File type to search (rg --type). Common types: js, py, rust, go, java, etc.","title":"Type"},"glob":{"anyOf":[{"type":"string"},{"type":"null"}],"default":null,"description":"Glob pattern to filter files (e.g. \"*.js\", \"*.{ts,tsx}\").","title":"Glob"},"output_mode":{"default":"content","description":"Output mode: \"content\", \"files_with_matches\", or \"count\"","title":"Output Mode","type":"string"},"-A":{"anyOf":[{"type":"integer"},{"type":"null"}],"default":null,"description":"Number of lines to show after each match","title":"-A"},"-B":{"anyOf":[{"type":"integer"},{"type":"null"}],"default":null,"description":"Number of lines to show before each match","title":"-B"},"-C":{"anyOf":[{"type":"integer"},{"type":"null"}],"default":null,"description":"Number of lines to show before and after each match","title":"-C"},"-i":{"default":false,"description":"Case insensitive search. Defaults to false","title":"-I","type":"boolean"},"multiline":{"default":false,"description":"Enable multiline mode where . matches newlines. Default: false.","title":"Multiline","type":"boolean"},"head_limit":{"anyOf":[{"type":"integer"},{"type":"null"}],"default":null,"description":"Limit output to first N lines/entries","title":"Head Limit"},"search_filenames":{"default":false,"description":"Search file names instead of file contents. Default: false.","title":"Search Filenames","type":"boolean"},"search_engine":{"default":false,"description":"Search engine files instead of game project files. Default: false.","title":"Search Engine","type":"boolean"}},"required":["pattern"],"title":"grepArguments"}},{"name":"quicksearch","description":"Quick search bridge that calls the mcp-client-chatbot /quicksearch endpoint.\n\n    This tool acts as a bridge to the mcp-client-chatbot server which performs\n    fast file path search using fast-glob and retrieves dependencies/referencers.\n    Results are truncated to 15k tokens to avoid overwhelming the context.\n\n    Args:\n        query: The search query string to look for in file paths\n        max_results: Maximum number of results to return (default: 10)\n\n    Returns:\n        JSON string containing search results with file paths and dependency/referencer information\n    ","inputSchema":{"type":"object","properties":{"query":{"title":"Query","type":"string"},"max_results":{"default":10,"title":"Max Results","type":"integer"}},"required":["query"],"title":"quicksearchArguments"}},{"name":"get_text_file_contents","description":"\n    Read contents from a text file with support for partial reading.\n    Primary use-case is for fetching code from text files such as txt, ini, cpp, h, inl, html, css, js, etc.\n    Prefer to query less than 100 lines at a time and only read as much as needed to answer the user's question.\n    Consider using grep first to fetch code snippets with their line numbers to help get contextual line info before deciding where in the file to requests lines from.\n    Args:\n        full_file_path: Full path to the text file to read\n        line_start: Line number to start reading from (1-indexed, default: 1)\n        num_lines: Number of lines to fetch starting from line_start (default: 50)\n    Returns:\n        JSON string containing:\n        - total_line_count: Total number of lines in the full file\n        - fetched_line_count: Number of lines fetched by this call\n        - lines: Array of line strings (without newline characters)\n    ","inputSchema":{"type":"object","properties":{"full_file_path":{"title":"Full File Path","type":"string"},"line_start":{"default":1,"title":"Line Start","type":"integer"},"num_lines":{"default":50,"title":"Num Lines","type":"integer"}},"required":["full_file_path"],"title":"get_text_file_contentsArguments"}},{"name":"create_or_edit_plan","description":"\n    Unreal Engine Game Development Tool: Create or Edit Plan\n\n    Create a versioned plan file for Plan Mode.\n\n    Plans are structured markdown documents that outline steps for implementing\n    features or fixing problems. The plan is persisted as a versioned file in\n    Saved/.Aura/plans/ and rendered in the UI with a \"Build\" button for execution.\n\n    Each call creates a new version: plan_name_v1.md, plan_name_v2.md, etc.\n\n    Args:\n        markdown_text: The full markdown content of the plan. Use checkboxes\n                      (- [ ]) for each step. Include code snippets, file paths,\n                      and approach details where helpful.\n        plan_name: Base name for the plan file, you must always use random words instead of a relevant name to avoid collisions(e.g., \"player_movement\" -> player_movement_v1.md).\n                  Will be sanitized to lowercase alphanumeric with underscores.\n        title: Optional display title for the plan. Defaults to the plan name in title case.\n\n    Returns:\n        JSON object with plan content for UI rendering in PlanUI component,\n        including version number and file path.\n    ","inputSchema":{"type":"object","properties":{"markdown_text":{"title":"Markdown Text","type":"string"},"plan_name":{"title":"Plan Name","type":"string"},"title":{"anyOf":[{"type":"string"},{"type":"null"}],"default":null,"title":"Title"}},"required":["markdown_text","plan_name"],"title":"create_or_edit_planArguments"}},{"name":"generate_images","description":"\n    Generate AI images and save them to the project.\n\n    The backend selects the OpenAI image model per capability:\n      - `background_transparency=\"transparent\"` routes to gpt-image-1.5 for real\n        alpha-channel PNG output (gpt-image-2 cannot emit alpha).\n      - Everything else routes to gpt-image-2 (better text rendering, improved\n        composition, higher resolution).\n    This is fully server-side; callers do not need to specify a model.\n\n    **REQUIRED PARAMETER - images**: You MUST provide an array of image specifications.\n    This parameter is MANDATORY - the tool will fail without it.\n\n    EXAMPLE CALL:\n    {\n        \"images\": [\n            {\n                \"name\": \"forest_background\",\n                \"description\": \"A mystical forest with tall trees and fog\"\n            }\n        ],\n        \"aspect_ratio\": \"landscape\",\n        \"quality\": \"high\"\n    }\n\n    WHEN TO USE THIS TOOL:\n    - User asks to create a brand new image from scratch\n    - User describes an entirely new scene with no reference to existing images\n\n    WHEN TO USE edit_images INSTEAD:\n    - User asks to modify, tweak, or change an existing image\n    - User asks to add/remove elements from an existing image\n    - User provides an image and wants changes applied to it\n\n    GENERATING VARIATIONS:\n    - Set variations=N to generate N different interpretations of each image description\n    - Each variation uses the same prompt but produces a unique result\n    - Useful for: logo concepts, color schemes, style exploration, A/B testing designs\n    - Example: {\"images\": [{\"name\": \"logo\", \"description\": \"Modern tech company logo\"}], \"variations\": 4}\n      → Generates 4 different logo variations in a single API call\n\n    Returns status information about the image generation and saving process for each image.\n\n    Args:\n        images: **[REQUIRED]** List of image specifications. Each dictionary MUST contain:\n            - name (string, required): The filename for the generated image\n            - description (string, required): Detailed description of what to generate\n        aspect_ratio (optional): Image aspect ratio. Options: \"square\" (1024x1024), \"landscape\" (1536x1024), \"portrait\" (1024x1536). Default: \"square\"\n        background_transparency (optional): \"opaque\" or \"transparent\". Default: \"opaque\"\n        quality (optional): Image quality - \"auto\", \"low\", \"medium\", or \"high\". Default: \"auto\"\n        moderation (optional): Content moderation - \"auto\" or \"low\". Default: \"auto\"\n        variations (optional): Number of variations to generate per image (1-10, default: 1).\n            When >1, generates multiple different interpretations of each description in a single API call.\n\n    Returns:\n        JSON with generation results including successful/failed image counts and saved file paths.\n    ","inputSchema":{"type":"object","properties":{"images":{"items":{"additionalProperties":true,"type":"object"},"title":"Images","type":"array"},"aspect_ratio":{"default":"square","title":"Aspect Ratio","type":"string"},"background_transparency":{"default":"opaque","title":"Background Transparency","type":"string"},"quality":{"default":"auto","title":"Quality","type":"string"},"moderation":{"default":"auto","title":"Moderation","type":"string"},"variations":{"default":1,"title":"Variations","type":"integer"},"cancellation_token":{"anyOf":[{"type":"string"},{"type":"null"}],"default":null,"title":"Cancellation Token"}},"required":["images"],"title":"generate_imagesArguments"}},{"name":"edit_images","description":"\n    Edit or extend images using OpenAI's image edit API.\n\n    The backend selects the model per capability:\n      - `background=\"transparent\"` routes to gpt-image-1.5, which natively emits\n        PNGs with an alpha channel. `input_fidelity` is forwarded as a real API\n        parameter on this path and controls source-preservation strictly.\n      - Anything else routes to gpt-image-2 (better text rendering and detail\n        quality). gpt-image-2 removed `input_fidelity` as an API parameter, so\n        the backend translates \"high\"/\"low\" into prompt additions that approximate\n        the same steering.\n    If `background=\"transparent\"` is selected with an incompatible output_format\n    (e.g., jpeg), the backend forces png/webp so the returned file actually\n    carries alpha. This is all server-side — callers do not specify a model.\n\n    WHEN TO USE THIS TOOL:\n    - User asks to modify, tweak, adjust, or change an existing image\n    - User asks to \"make it more/less [adjective]\" referring to a previously generated image\n    - User asks to add/remove elements from an existing image\n    - User provides an image and wants changes applied to it\n\n    WHEN TO USE generate_images INSTEAD:\n    - User asks to create a brand new image from scratch\n    - User describes an entirely new scene with no reference to existing images\n    - No previous image is being referenced\n\n    ITERATIVE EDITING WORKFLOW:\n    - When editing a previously generated image, use the full_path from the prior generate_images or edit_images result\n    - Set input_fidelity to \"high\" when the user wants to preserve faces, logos, or specific details\n    - You can chain multiple edit_images calls for incremental refinements\n\n    IMPORTANT USAGE RULES:\n    - If the user does not specify an image to edit, ask the user to specify.\n    - Always use the full file paths to the images.\n    - Use get_recent_generated_images to find recently generated/edited image paths.\n\n    FINDING IMAGE FILE PATHS:\n    - This tool requires full file system paths (e.g., \"D:/Projects/.../Content/Generated_Images/image.png\"), NOT UObject paths (e.g., \"/Game/Generated_Images/image\").\n    - If you only have a UObject path or asset name from context, use query_unreal_project_assets with the image name to find the full file path.\n    - Example: If context shows \"/Game/Generated_Images/ad_car01\", call query_unreal_project_assets(\"ad_car01\") to get the full path.\n    - Generated images are typically saved in the project's Content/Generated_Images folder or Saved/generated_images folder.\n\n    Args:\n        input_images: List of file paths to input images (1-16 images max)\n            Supported formats: PNG, WEBP, JPG. Max size: 50MB each.\n            Use full file paths to the images (NOT UObject paths like /Game/...).\n        prompt: Description of desired edits (up to 32,000 characters)\n            Be specific about what changes you want to make to the images.\n        background: Background handling - \"transparent\", \"opaque\", or \"auto\" (default)\n            Controls transparency in the output image.\n        mask_image: Optional PNG mask file path for selective editing\n            Transparent areas in the mask indicate where edits should be applied.\n            Must have same dimensions as the first input image.\n        quality: Image quality - \"high\", \"medium\", \"low\", or \"auto\" (default)\n        size: Output size - \"1024x1024\", \"1536x1024\", \"1024x1536\", or \"auto\" (default)\n        output_format: Output format - \"png\" (default), \"jpeg\", or \"webp\"\n        output_compression: Compression level 0-100% (for webp/jpeg only, default: 100)\n        n: Number of edited images to generate (1-10, default: 1)\n        input_fidelity: Fidelity level for preserving input image details - \"high\" or \"low\" (default).\n            Use \"high\" to better preserve faces, logos, text, and fine details from the input images.\n\n    Returns:\n        JSON string with edit results and saved file paths\n    ","inputSchema":{"type":"object","properties":{"input_images":{"items":{"type":"string"},"title":"Input Images","type":"array"},"prompt":{"title":"Prompt","type":"string"},"background":{"default":"auto","title":"Background","type":"string"},"mask_image":{"default":"","title":"Mask Image","type":"string"},"quality":{"default":"auto","title":"Quality","type":"string"},"size":{"default":"auto","title":"Size","type":"string"},"output_format":{"default":"png","title":"Output Format","type":"string"},"output_compression":{"default":100,"title":"Output Compression","type":"integer"},"n":{"default":1,"title":"N","type":"integer"},"input_fidelity":{"default":"low","title":"Input Fidelity","type":"string"},"cancellation_token":{"anyOf":[{"type":"string"},{"type":"null"}],"default":null,"title":"Cancellation Token"},"input_images_base64":{"anyOf":[{"items":{"type":"string"},"type":"array"},{"type":"null"}],"default":null,"title":"Input Images Base64"},"mask_image_base64":{"anyOf":[{"type":"string"},{"type":"null"}],"default":null,"title":"Mask Image Base64"},"return_base64":{"default":false,"title":"Return Base64","type":"boolean"}},"required":["input_images","prompt"],"title":"edit_imagesArguments"}},{"name":"get_recent_generated_images","description":"Get file paths of recently generated or edited images in this session.\n\n    Use this to find images for editing when the user references a previously generated image.\n    Returns a list of full file paths, most recent first.\n    ","inputSchema":{"type":"object","properties":{},"title":"get_recent_generated_imagesArguments"}},{"name":"generate_model_from_text","description":"\n    Generate a 3D model from a text description.\n    This tool directly calls the Vercel backend endpoints without going through the local server .\n\n    Models are imported into the project as a static mesh asset. The default save location is `/Game/AuraModelGen/{ModelName}/{ModelName}`.\n    Users can customize the save folder using Unreal Editor: Editor Preferences. In that case the final save location will be `/Game/{CustomSaveFolder}/{ModelName}/{ModelName}`.\n\n    IMPORTANT USAGE RULES:\n    - Keep description under 1024 characters (will be truncated if longer)\n    - Keep negative_prompt under 255 characters (will be truncated if longer)\n    - When users say \"no grass\", \"no horns\", \"without smooth surfaces\", etc. → use negative_prompt parameter\n    - User requests like \"avoid X\" or \"exclude Y\" should go in negative_prompt, not description\n    - Never set PBR to true unless the user explicitly asks for it.\n\n    AUTOSCALE BEHAVIOR (LLM):\n    - If the user does not provide estimated_scale (or it remains 1.0), infer a reasonable\n      value from the description using typical real-world sizes: Small 0.1-0.3m, Medium 0.5-2.0m,\n      Large 2.0-8.0m, Very large 10.0m+.\n    - Set the inferred value in the estimated_scale parameter. Do not embed these guidelines or any\n      inferred value into the description.\n\n    On failure: Report the error to the user and let them decide whether to retry. Do not automatically\n    retry this tool or fall back to generate_model_from_image() as a workaround. These are time-consuming\n    operations and the user should choose how to proceed.\n\n    Parameters:\n    - model_name: The name of the 3D model to generate\n    - description: The text prompt describing the 3D model to generate (max 1024 characters)\n    - negative_prompt: Text describing what to avoid in the generated model (max 255 characters, optional)\n    - face_limit: Target face count limit (0 = Auto, optional)\n      LLM DEFAULT BEHAVIOR: Unless the user explicitly requests \"high detail\", \"maximum quality\",\n      \"highest resolution\", or specifies a different face count, ALWAYS set face_limit=50000\n      to ensure reasonable mesh complexity for Unreal Engine performance. Only use face_limit=0\n      (Auto) when the user explicitly requests maximum quality or \"no face limit\".\n      Note: face_limit is auto-clamped to each mode's valid range:\n        - P1-20260311 (default): 48-20000\n        - quad=True: 500-5000\n      If P1 is selected (default, or via the user's forced version setting), a value\n      above 20000 will be clamped down to 20000. The Tripo API rejects out-of-range values.\n    - pbr: Whether to generate PBR materials (default: False, optional)\n    - estimated_scale: Estimated longest dimension in meters for real-world scaling (default: 1.0 = no scaling)\n    - pivot_position: Pivot position for the mesh - \"Center\", \"Bottom\", or \"Target\" (default: \"Bottom\")\n    - quad: Generate quad mesh output (forces FBX format when True, default: False, optional)\n    - convert_to_fbx: Convert GLB result to FBX format (ignored if quad=True, default: True, optional)\n    - smooth_angle: Optional smoothing angle in degrees (0-180) to apply to mesh normals during import (default: None = no smoothing, optional)\n    - store_metadata: Whether to write generation metadata (task_id, parameters) to the asset for future reference (default: True, optional)\n    - pose_type: Pose type for character/humanoid models (default: \"Default\")\n      Valid values: \"Default\", \"A-pose\", \"T-pose\"\n\n      LLM POSE DETECTION BEHAVIOR:\n      - Detect pose requests from ANY of these variations (case-insensitive):\n        A-pose: \"A-pose\", \"A pose\", \"Apose\", \"a-pose\", \"apose\", \"a pose\"\n        T-pose: \"T-pose\", \"T pose\", \"Tpose\", \"t-pose\", \"tpose\", \"t pose\"\n      - If user explicitly requests A-pose, set pose_type to \"A-pose\"\n      - If user explicitly requests T-pose using any variation above, set pose_type to \"T-pose\"\n      - If the user does NOT explicitly request a pose, leave pose_type as \"Default\" regardless of model type\n      - Do NOT include pose instructions in the description — the system injects pose details automatically.\n\n    - rig_model: Whether to rig the model for animation (default: False).\n      When True, the model will be processed through the rigging pipeline to create a SkeletalMesh.\n      NOTE: Character models default to \"A-pose\" for UE mannequin skeleton compatibility, which is also optimal for rigging.\n      Only applies when the user explicitly requests rigging using terms like \"rig\", \"rigged\", \"skeleton\",\n      or \"skeletal mesh\". A T-pose or A-pose request alone does not imply rigging — poses are valid for\n      static meshes. Similarly, requesting a character or humanoid model does not imply rigging.\n      Previous rigged model generations in the same conversation do not carry over to subsequent requests.\n\n    - model_version: Which model generation version to use (default: \"auto\")\n      Valid values: \"auto\", \"v2.5\", \"v3.0\", \"p1\"\n      - \"auto\": Uses P1 (game-ready, optimized for clean topology). The user's Force settings may override this.\n      - \"v3.0\": High-detail generation (v3.0-20250812). Use ONLY when user explicitly says \"V3\", \"use V3\", \"high poly\", or \"high detail\".\n      - \"v2.5\": Legacy standard generation (v2.5-20250123). Only used when user explicitly says \"V2\", \"V2.5\", \"use V2\", or \"use V2.5\".\n      - \"p1\": Same as \"auto\". Explicit alias for P1 generation.\n      Leave as \"auto\" for all other requests.\n\n    Returns:\n    - Information about the generated model including status, model_name, and asset_path\n    ","inputSchema":{"type":"object","properties":{"model_name":{"title":"Model Name","type":"string"},"description":{"title":"Description","type":"string"},"negative_prompt":{"default":"","title":"Negative Prompt","type":"string"},"face_limit":{"default":0,"title":"Face Limit","type":"integer"},"pbr":{"default":false,"title":"Pbr","type":"boolean"},"estimated_scale":{"default":1,"title":"Estimated Scale","type":"number"},"pivot_position":{"default":"Bottom","title":"Pivot Position","type":"string"},"quad":{"default":false,"title":"Quad","type":"boolean"},"convert_to_fbx":{"default":true,"title":"Convert To Fbx","type":"boolean"},"smooth_angle":{"anyOf":[{"type":"number"},{"type":"null"}],"default":null,"title":"Smooth Angle"},"store_metadata":{"default":true,"title":"Store Metadata","type":"boolean"},"pose_type":{"default":"Default","title":"Pose Type","type":"string"},"rig_model":{"default":false,"title":"Rig Model","type":"boolean"},"model_version":{"default":"auto","title":"Model Version","type":"string"},"cancellation_token":{"anyOf":[{"type":"string"},{"type":"null"}],"default":null,"title":"Cancellation Token"}},"required":["model_name","description"],"title":"generate_model_from_textArguments"}},{"name":"generate_model_from_image","description":"\n    Generate a 3D model from a PNG, JPG, or JPEG image.\n    This tool directly calls the Vercel backend endpoints without going through the local server.\n\n    Models are imported into the project as a static mesh asset to the default soft path `Game/AuraModelGen/{ModelName}/{ModelName}` or\n    or the soft path provided by the user.\n\n    <IMPORTANT> DO NOT generate a model unless the user explicitly asks to do so. If the user asks to generate a model immediately after generating an image, use this tool to generate a model from the generated image.\n    If the image choice is unspecified or ambiguous (no clear image to use or multiple candidates), PAUSE and ask the user to\n    confirm/provide the precise image before calling this tool. DO NOT guess or auto-select.\n\n    On failure: If this tool fails to generate a model, DO NOT CALL generate_model_from_text() to try and generate the model.\n    STOP IMMEDIATELY and inform the user that the model generation failed. DO NOT attempt any workarounds.\n    The generate_model_from_text() tool is FORBIDDEN as a fallback when this tool fails.\n\n\n    Parameters:\n    - model_name: The name of the 3D model to generate\n    - image_file: filestystem path or Unreal Engine soft path to a .png, .jpg, or .jpeg image file\n    - pbr: Whether to generate PBR materials (default: False, optional)\n    - estimated_scale: Estimated longest dimension in meters for real-world scaling (default: 1.0 = no scaling, optional)\n      SCALE ESTIMATION GUIDE: Look at the image and estimate the real-world size:\n      * Small items (mugs, phones, jewelry): 0.1-0.3m\n      * Medium objects (furniture, appliances, tools): 0.5-2.0m\n      * Large objects (cars, equipment, large furniture): 2.0-8.0m\n      * Very large objects (buildings, vehicles, structures): 10.0m+\n      IMPORTANT: Set estimated_scale to the appropriate value based on what you see in the image\n    - pivot_position: Pivot position for the mesh - \"Center\", \"Bottom\", or \"Target\" (default: \"Bottom\", optional)\n    - face_limit: Target face count limit (0 = Auto, optional)\n      LLM DEFAULT BEHAVIOR: Unless the user explicitly requests \"high detail\", \"maximum quality\",\n      \"highest resolution\", or specifies a different face count, ALWAYS set face_limit=50000\n      to ensure reasonable mesh complexity for Unreal Engine performance. Only use face_limit=0\n      (Auto) when the user explicitly requests maximum quality or \"no face limit\".\n      Note: face_limit is auto-clamped to each mode's valid range:\n        - P1-20260311 (default): 48-20000\n        - quad=True: 500-5000\n      If P1 is selected (default, or via the user's forced version setting), a value\n      above 20000 will be clamped down to 20000. The Tripo API rejects out-of-range values.\n    - quad: Generate quad mesh output (forces FBX format when True, default: False, optional)\n    - convert_to_fbx: Convert GLB result to FBX format (ignored if quad=True, default: True, optional)\n    - smooth_angle: Optional smoothing angle in degrees (0-180) to apply to mesh normals during import (default: None = no smoothing, optional)\n    - store_metadata: Whether to write generation metadata (task_id, parameters) to the asset for future reference (default: True, optional)\n    - rig_model: Whether to rig the model for animation (default: False).\n      When True, the model will be processed through the rigging pipeline to create a SkeletalMesh.\n      Only applies when the user explicitly requests rigging using terms like \"rig\", \"rigged\", \"skeleton\",\n      or \"skeletal mesh\". An image showing a T-pose or A-pose character does not imply rigging.\n      Similarly, the image containing a character or humanoid does not imply rigging.\n      Previous rigged model generations in the same conversation do not carry over to subsequent requests.\n\n    - model_version: Which model generation version to use (default: \"auto\")\n      Valid values: \"auto\", \"v2.5\", \"v3.0\", \"p1\"\n      - \"auto\": Uses P1 (game-ready, optimized for clean topology). The user's Force settings may override this.\n      - \"v3.0\": High-detail generation (v3.0-20250812). Use ONLY when user explicitly says \"V3\", \"use V3\", \"high poly\", or \"high detail\".\n      - \"v2.5\": Legacy standard generation (v2.5-20250123). Only used when user explicitly says \"V2\", \"V2.5\", \"use V2\", or \"use V2.5\".\n      - \"p1\": Same as \"auto\". Explicit alias for P1 generation.\n      Leave as \"auto\" for all other requests.\n\n    Returns:\n    - Information about the generated model including status, model_name, and asset_path\n    ","inputSchema":{"type":"object","properties":{"model_name":{"title":"Model Name","type":"string"},"image_file":{"title":"Image File","type":"string"},"pbr":{"default":false,"title":"Pbr","type":"boolean"},"estimated_scale":{"default":1,"title":"Estimated Scale","type":"number"},"pivot_position":{"default":"Bottom","title":"Pivot Position","type":"string"},"face_limit":{"default":0,"title":"Face Limit","type":"integer"},"quad":{"default":false,"title":"Quad","type":"boolean"},"convert_to_fbx":{"default":true,"title":"Convert To Fbx","type":"boolean"},"smooth_angle":{"anyOf":[{"type":"number"},{"type":"null"}],"default":null,"title":"Smooth Angle"},"store_metadata":{"default":true,"title":"Store Metadata","type":"boolean"},"rig_model":{"default":false,"title":"Rig Model","type":"boolean"},"model_version":{"default":"auto","title":"Model Version","type":"string"},"cancellation_token":{"anyOf":[{"type":"string"},{"type":"null"}],"default":null,"title":"Cancellation Token"}},"required":["model_name","image_file"],"title":"generate_model_from_imageArguments"}},{"name":"rig_model_from_mesh","description":"\n    Rig an existing static mesh using Aura's animation pipeline.\n\n    Supports both:\n    1. Models with Aura generation metadata (uses stored task ID directly)\n    2. Models without metadata (exports to FBX and imports for processing)\n\n    <IMPORTANT>\n    If this tool fails to rig a model, DO NOT attempt to call generate_model_from_text or\n    generate_model_from_image to create a new rigged model. DO NOT retry this tool automatically.\n    STOP and inform the user that rigging failed for this specific model, then ask what they would like to do next.\n    Using generate_model_from_text/image as a fallback is FORBIDDEN.\n    </IMPORTANT>\n\n    Args:\n        asset_path: Soft path to the UStaticMesh (e.g., \"/Game/AuraModelGen/MyModel/MyModel\")\n        output_name: Optional name for rigged model (defaults to the original asset name)\n        estimated_scale: Scale factor for import (inherits from original metadata if not provided, defaults to 1.0)\n        pivot_position: Pivot position - \"Center\", \"Bottom\", or \"Target\" (inherits from metadata, defaults to \"Bottom\")\n        store_metadata: Whether to store generation metadata on the rigged asset (default: True)\n        cancellation_token: Optional token for cancellation support\n\n    Returns:\n        JSON with status, asset_path, and rigging information\n    ","inputSchema":{"type":"object","properties":{"asset_path":{"title":"Asset Path","type":"string"},"output_name":{"anyOf":[{"type":"string"},{"type":"null"}],"default":null,"title":"Output Name"},"estimated_scale":{"anyOf":[{"type":"number"},{"type":"null"}],"default":null,"title":"Estimated Scale"},"pivot_position":{"anyOf":[{"type":"string"},{"type":"null"}],"default":null,"title":"Pivot Position"},"store_metadata":{"default":true,"title":"Store Metadata","type":"boolean"},"cancellation_token":{"anyOf":[{"type":"string"},{"type":"null"}],"default":null,"title":"Cancellation Token"}},"required":["asset_path"],"title":"rig_model_from_meshArguments"}},{"name":"read_datatable_keys","description":"\n    Read the keys of a datatable from the project.\n\n    You must provide the soft path from the project root to the data table file.\n    Do not use a relative path, instead use a soft path.\n    e.g. don't use: Content/MyFolder/MyDataTable.uasset\n    use: /Game/MyFolder/MyDataTable\n\n    asset_path: The path to the data table file.\n    ","inputSchema":{"type":"object","properties":{"asset_path":{"title":"Asset Path","type":"string"}},"required":["asset_path"],"title":"read_datatable_keysArguments"}},{"name":"read_datatable_values","description":"\n    Read the values of a datatable from the project.\n\n    You must provide the soft path from the project root to the data table file.\n    Do not use a relative path, instead use a soft path.\n    e.g. don't use: Content/MyFolder/MyDataTable.uasset\n    use: /Game/MyFolder/MyDataTable\n\n    asset_path: The path to the data table file.\n    row_names: The names of the rows to read values for.\n    ","inputSchema":{"type":"object","properties":{"asset_path":{"title":"Asset Path","type":"string"},"row_names":{"items":{"type":"string"},"title":"Row Names","type":"array"}},"required":["asset_path","row_names"],"title":"read_datatable_valuesArguments"}},{"name":"get_attribute_set","description":"\n    Get attribute sets and their attributes from the project.\n    Searches for UAttributeSet subclasses (from Gameplay Ability System) by name.\n    Returns all FGameplayAttributeData members for each matching attribute set class.\n\n    When called with an empty query, returns a high-level summary of available attribute sets.\n    Call again with a specific query to get detailed attributes for a particular set.\n\n    Args:\n        query: Space-delimited search terms to filter attribute sets by name.\n               Matches if ANY term is found (case-insensitive substring match).\n               If empty, returns a summary listing attribute set names only.\n        max_results: Maximum number of attribute sets to return in detail. Defaults to 10.\n\n    Returns:\n        Summary of attribute set names (empty query) or detailed attribute set data (with query).\n    ","inputSchema":{"type":"object","properties":{"query":{"default":"","title":"Query","type":"string"},"max_results":{"default":10,"title":"Max Results","type":"integer"}},"title":"get_attribute_setArguments"}},{"name":"get_gameplay_tags","description":"\n    Get gameplay tags from the project.\n    Searches for gameplay tags by name.\n\n    When called with an empty query, returns a high-level summary showing tag categories\n    (up to 2 levels deep). Call again with a specific query to see full tag names.\n\n    Args:\n        query: Space-delimited search terms to filter tags by name.\n               Matches if ANY term is found (case-insensitive substring match).\n               If empty, returns a category summary instead of all tags.\n        max_results: Maximum number of tags to return when using a query. Defaults to 10.\n\n    Returns:\n        Category summary (empty query) or matching tag names (with query).\n    ","inputSchema":{"type":"object","properties":{"query":{"default":"","title":"Query","type":"string"},"max_results":{"default":10,"title":"Max Results","type":"integer"}},"title":"get_gameplay_tagsArguments"}},{"name":"get_enums","description":"\n    Get enums and their entries from the project.\n    Searches for UEnum types by name.\n\n    When called with an empty query, returns a list of enum names only (without entries).\n    Call again with a specific query to get the entries for particular enums.\n\n    Args:\n        query: Space-delimited search terms to filter enums by name.\n               Matches if ANY term is found (case-insensitive substring match).\n               If empty, returns a summary listing enum names only.\n        max_results: Maximum number of enums to return with full entries. Defaults to 10.\n\n    Returns:\n        Summary of enum names (empty query) or detailed enum data with entries (with query).\n    ","inputSchema":{"type":"object","properties":{"query":{"default":"","title":"Query","type":"string"},"max_results":{"default":10,"title":"Max Results","type":"integer"}},"title":"get_enumsArguments"}},{"name":"get_blueprint_properties_specifiers","description":"Get the specifiers for a list of properties in a blueprint.\n\n    Parameters:\n    - soft_path_from_project_root: The path to the blueprint file relative to the project root\n    - property_names: The names of the properties to get specifiers for\n\n    Returns:\n    - JSON string containing the property specifiers, flags, metadata, and type information\n    ","inputSchema":{"type":"object","properties":{"soft_path_from_project_root":{"title":"Soft Path From Project Root","type":"string"},"property_names":{"items":{"type":"string"},"title":"Property Names","type":"array"}},"required":["soft_path_from_project_root","property_names"],"title":"get_blueprint_properties_specifiersArguments"}},{"name":"get_blueprint_material_properties","description":"\n    Get the material properties of a blueprint.\n\n    Parameters:\n    - soft_path_from_project_root: The path to the blueprint file relative to the project root\n    ","inputSchema":{"type":"object","properties":{"soft_path_from_project_root":{"title":"Soft Path From Project Root","type":"string"}},"required":["soft_path_from_project_root"],"title":"get_blueprint_material_propertiesArguments"}},{"name":"cancel_operation","description":"\n    **[INTERNAL SYSTEM TOOL - DO NOT CALL DIRECTLY]**\n\n    This tool is reserved for client-side abort signal propagation only.\n    It is automatically invoked by the client when a user clicks the stop/cancel button.\n    The AI assistant should NEVER call this tool in response to user queries.\n\n    Technical Details:\n    - Cancels a long-running operation by marking its cancellation token as cancelled\n    - Only accepts cancellation tokens generated by the client's AbortController\n    - Called programmatically by remote-tool-executor.ts, not by LLM tool selection\n\n    Parameters:\n    - cancellation_token: The unique UUID token identifying the operation to cancel\n\n    Returns:\n    - Success or error message indicating if the operation was cancelled\n    ","inputSchema":{"type":"object","properties":{"cancellation_token":{"title":"Cancellation Token","type":"string"}},"required":["cancellation_token"],"title":"cancel_operationArguments"}},{"name":"launch_unreal_project","description":"Launch Unreal Engine in headless mode for the current project.\n\n    If no project_path is provided, auto-discovers the .uproject file by:\n    1. Walking up from the current working directory\n    2. Checking .Aura/project_path.txt (last known project)\n\n    The engine path is auto-resolved from the project's EngineAssociation.\n    If UE is already running, returns the current status instead of launching again.\n    ","inputSchema":{"type":"object","properties":{"project_path":{"default":"","title":"Project Path","type":"string"}},"title":"launch_unreal_projectArguments"}},{"name":"get_headless_status","description":"Get the current status of the headless Unreal Engine instance.\n\n    Returns the connection state:\n    - editor_connected: Full UE editor is open and connected\n    - editor_running_bridge_unreachable: Editor is open but bridge is not responding\n    - headless_running: Headless UE is running and ready\n    - headless_launching: Headless UE is starting up (with progress info)\n    - disconnected: No UE instance is running\n    ","inputSchema":{"type":"object","properties":{},"title":"get_headless_statusArguments"}},{"name":"shutdown_headless","description":"Shut down the headless Unreal Engine instance.\n\n    Sends a graceful shutdown request to the Python bridge, which then shuts down UE.\n    Falls back to force-killing the process if the bridge is unresponsive.\n\n    Refuses with status=\"refused\" when the editor has unsaved (dirty) packages\n    OR when the dirty-package check itself can't reach the bridge — the\n    fail-safe choice prevents silently losing AI-generated work. Pass\n    force=True to bypass and shut down anyway, discarding the unsaved work.\n\n    Args:\n      force: If True, shut down even when there are unsaved assets or the\n        dirty check failed. Default False — the safe choice; caller should save first.\n\n    Returns JSON. Possible statuses:\n      \"shutting_down\"   bridge accepted the graceful shutdown request\n      \"killed\"          bridge unreachable; the editor process was force-killed\n      \"not_running\"     no headless UE was found\n      \"refused\"         dirty packages exist OR dirty check failed (force=False)\n      \"failed\"          something went wrong while killing\n    ","inputSchema":{"type":"object","properties":{"force":{"default":false,"title":"Force","type":"boolean"}},"title":"shutdown_headlessArguments"}},{"name":"recompile_unreal_project","description":"Recompile the project's Editor target (Development / Win64) from C++ source.\n\n    USE ONLY IF:\n      1. You started UE yourself via `launch_unreal_project` (headless mode).\n         Do NOT run this against a UE instance the user opened themselves —\n         the tool shuts the editor down first and they may lose unsaved work.\n      2. You accept that any running headless instance will be shut down.\n         The tool calls `shutdown_headless`, waits for the process to fully\n         exit, and only then invokes UnrealBuildTool.\n\n    If a non-headless UnrealEditor.exe is detected, the tool refuses with\n    status=\"refused\" and does not touch anything.\n\n    Refuses with status=\"refused\" / reason=\"unsaved_assets\" when the running\n    headless editor has unsaved (dirty) packages, so AI-generated changes are\n    not silently lost during the shutdown step. Pass force=True to bypass.\n\n    Typical use case: `launch_unreal_project` exits quickly and the UE log\n    says \"Plugin X failed to load because module X could not be found\".\n    That means the plugin's DLLs are missing or stale. Call this tool to\n    rebuild them, then call `launch_unreal_project` again.\n\n    Args:\n      project_path: Optional absolute path to the .uproject. If omitted, the\n        same auto-discovery as launch_unreal_project is used.\n      timeout_seconds: Build timeout in seconds. Default 720 (12 min) to stay\n        under the MCP client's 13-minute call cap. Raising this above ~780\n        will not help unless the tool also emits progress notifications —\n        the client will hang up first.\n      force: If True, recompile even when the editor has unsaved assets\n        (the shutdown will discard them). Default False.\n\n    Returns JSON with fields:\n      status            \"success\" | \"failed\" | \"refused\"\n      exit_code         UBT exit code (0 on success)\n      duration_seconds  Build wall-clock time\n      errors            Parsed error lines (up to 50)\n      warnings          Parsed warning lines (up to 20)\n      log_tail          Last ~60 lines of UBT output\n      target            Editor target name that was built\n      engine_root       Resolved engine install directory\n      project           Resolved .uproject path\n\n    On success, call `launch_unreal_project` again to start the rebuilt\n    editor. On failure, read the `errors` field — most failures are C++\n    compile errors in project or plugin source.\n    ","inputSchema":{"type":"object","properties":{"project_path":{"default":"","title":"Project Path","type":"string"},"timeout_seconds":{"default":720,"title":"Timeout Seconds","type":"integer"},"force":{"default":false,"title":"Force","type":"boolean"}},"title":"recompile_unreal_projectArguments"}}]},{"name":"unreal_editor","config":{"command":"C:/Program Files/Epic Games/UE_5.7/Engine/Plugins/Marketplace/Aura/PortablePython/Windows/python.exe","args":["C:/Program Files/Epic Games/UE_5.7/Engine/Plugins/Marketplace/Aura/MCP/unreal_editor.py"]},"status":"connected","toolInfo":[{"name":"edit_todo_list","description":"\n    Edit todo items using a compact batch string.\n\n    Format:\n        \"index[,priorityCode][,statusCode]|index[,priorityCode][,statusCode]|...\"\n\n    Examples:\n        - \"0,m,ip|3,h,c\" → index 0: medium + in_progress; index 3: high + completed\n        - \"1,,ip\" → index 1: set in_progress, keep existing priority\n        - \"2,h\" → index 2: set high priority, keep existing status\n\n    Args:\n        codes: Compact string describing edits\n\n    Behavior:\n        - Requires an existing list (create via create_new_todo_list).\n        - Each segment must include an index; priority and/or status are optional.\n        - Returns the full updated list in todolist content format for display, with summary stats.\n    ","inputSchema":{"type":"object","properties":{"codes":{"title":"Codes","type":"string"}},"required":["codes"],"title":"edit_todo_listArguments"}},{"name":"create_new_todo_list","description":"\n    Create or replace the entire todo list with provided items.\n\n    This writes the full list in a minimal, line-based format, where each item is:\n        \"priority|status|description\"\n\n    Notes:\n        - Priorities: \"low\" | \"medium\" | \"high\"\n        - Statuses: \"not_started\" | \"in_progress\" | \"completed\"\n        - This is the tool to call for creating or resetting the list.\n        - The UI will render the returned todolist content; no need to restate it in messages.\n\n    Args:\n        todo_list_data: List of strings in the format above.\n\n    Example input for the tool call:\n    {\n        \"todo_list_data\": [\n            \"low|not_started|This is a description of a todo item\",\n            \"medium|in_progress|This is another description of a todo item\",\n            \"high|completed|This is a third description of a todo item\"\n        ]\n    }\n    ","inputSchema":{"type":"object","properties":{"todo_list_data":{"items":{"type":"string"},"title":"Todo List Data","type":"array"}},"required":["todo_list_data"],"title":"create_new_todo_listArguments"}},{"name":"get_todo_list","description":"\n    Get the current todo list as minimal lines and parsed display data.\n\n    Notes:\n        - Format per line: \"priority|status|description\"\n        - Use create_new_todo_list to initialize or replace the list.\n        - Use edit_todo_list to minimally update an item's status/priority by index.\n\n    Returns JSON with:\n        - success: bool\n        - todo_list_data: list[str] raw minimal lines\n        - content: [{ type: \"todolist\", data: ParsedItems }]\n    ","inputSchema":{"type":"object","properties":{},"title":"get_todo_listArguments"}},{"name":"edit_enumeration","description":"\n    Do not use a relative path, instead use a soft path.\n    e.g. don't use: Content/MyFolder/MyEnum.uasset\n    use: /Game/MyFolder/MyEnum\n\n    Args:\n        soft_path: The path to the enumeration to edit\n        enum_fields: List of string values for the enumeration (e.g., [\"Red\", \"Green\", \"Blue\"])\n\n    Returns:\n        JSON string containing the result of the enumeration editing\n\n    Example:\n        edit_enumeration(\"/Game/Enums/ColorEnum\", [\"Red\", \"Green\", \"Blue\", \"Yellow\"])\n    ","inputSchema":{"type":"object","properties":{"soft_path":{"title":"Soft Path","type":"string"},"enum_fields":{"items":{"type":"string"},"title":"Enum Fields","type":"array"}},"required":["soft_path","enum_fields"],"title":"edit_enumerationArguments"}},{"name":"edit_structure","description":"\n    Edit an existing blueprint structure incrementally. Only fields you mention are affected — all other fields are preserved untouched.\n\n    Operations:\n    - Add fields: Include new field names in `properties` with default values (provide type_hints for correct typing)\n    - Update defaults: Include existing field names in `properties` with new default values (type is preserved).\n      Supported default value types: bool, int, float, string, name, text, byte, enums (by value name),\n      common structs (Vector, Rotator, Quat, Color, LinearColor, Vector2D, Vector4, IntVector, IntPoint — as arrays or objects),\n      and containers (Array as JSON array, Set as JSON array, Map as JSON object with string keys).\n    - Change types: Provide a type_hint in properties_settings.type_hints. Optionally include the field in `properties` with a new default.\n      If the field is not in `properties`, the type changes and the default resets to the new type's zero value.\n    - Remove fields: List field names in properties_settings.remove_properties\n    - Rename fields: Provide old->new name mappings in properties_settings.renames\n\n    Fields NOT mentioned in any of these are left completely untouched — their types, defaults, and Blueprint connections are preserved.\n\n    You must provide the soft path from the project root to the structure file.\n    Do not use a relative path, instead use a soft path.\n    e.g. don't use: Content/MyFolder/MyStructure.uasset\n    use: /Game/MyFolder/MyStructure\n\n    Args:\n        soft_path: The path to the existing structure file to edit.\n        properties: Dictionary of field names to default values. Only include fields you want to add or whose defaults you want to update.\n            Existing fields not included here are preserved as-is.\n        properties_settings: Dictionary controlling how properties are handled.\n            - \"type_hints\": Dictionary of field names to type hint strings.\n                Required for new fields (unless auto-detection from the JSON value is acceptable).\n                For existing fields, only provide a type_hint if you want to CHANGE the type.\n                If omitted for an existing field, the current type is preserved.\n\n                Supported type hint formats:\n\n                Basic Types:\n                - \"bool\" or \"Boolean\"\n                - \"int\", \"int32\", or \"Integer\"\n                - \"float\" or \"Float\"\n                - \"double\" or \"Double\"\n                - \"string\", \"String\", or \"FString\"\n                - \"name\", \"Name\", or \"FName\"\n                - \"text\", \"Text\", or \"FText\"\n                - \"byte\", \"Byte\", or \"uint8\"\n                - \"int64\" or \"Int64\"\n\n                Common Unreal Structs (can use with or without F prefix):\n                - \"Vector\", \"FVector\", \"Vector2D\", \"FVector2D\", \"Vector4\", \"FVector4\"\n                - \"Rotator\", \"FRotator\", \"Transform\", \"FTransform\", \"Quat\", \"FQuat\"\n                - \"Color\", \"FColor\", \"LinearColor\", \"FLinearColor\"\n                - \"Guid\", \"FGuid\", \"DateTime\", \"FDateTime\", \"Timespan\", \"FTimespan\"\n                - \"IntVector\", \"FIntVector\", \"IntPoint\", \"FIntPoint\"\n\n                Any Unreal Engine Type (uses reflection system):\n                - Any UStruct name: \"GameplayTag\", \"GameplayAttribute\", etc.\n                - Any UClass name: \"StaticMesh\", \"Material\", \"Texture2D\", \"PlayerController\", etc. Don't include the U prefix, or a * prefix.\n                - Any UEnum name: \"ECollisionChannel\", \"EInputEvent\", etc.\n\n                Explicit Path References:\n                - \"struct:/Game/Path/To/MyStruct.MyStruct\" User-defined struct\n                - \"enum:/Game/Path/To/MyEnum.MyEnum\"  User-defined enum\n                - \"class:/Game/Path/To/MyClass.MyClass_C\" User-defined class\n                - \"softclass:/Game/Path/To/MyClass.MyClass\"\n                - \"object:/Game/Path/To/MyClass.MyClass\"\n                - \"softobject:/Game/Path/To/MyClass.MyClass\"\n\n                Container Types:\n                - \"array:ElementType\" - Array of ElementType (e.g., \"array:int\", \"array:Vector\", \"array:struct:/Game/MyStruct\")\n                - \"set:ElementType\" - Set of ElementType (e.g., \"set:string\", \"set:GameplayTag\")\n                - \"map:KeyType,ValueType\" - Map with KeyType keys and ValueType values (e.g., \"map:string,float\")\n                Map containers cannot contain other container types! To do nested containers, you must wrap those nested containers in a custom struct type.\n\n            - \"remove_properties\": List of field names to remove from the structure.\n            - \"renames\": Dictionary mapping old field names to new field names. Renames are processed first.\n\n    Returns:\n        JSON string containing the result of the structure editing operation\n\n    Examples:\n        # Add a new field to an existing structure (other fields untouched)\n        edit_structure(\n            \"/Game/Structs/PlayerData\",\n            {\"NewField\": \"default value\"},\n            {\"type_hints\": {\"NewField\": \"string\"}}\n        )\n\n        # Update default value of an existing field (type preserved)\n        edit_structure(\n            \"/Game/Structs/PlayerData\",\n            {\"Health\": 200.0},\n            {}\n        )\n\n        # Change an existing field's type\n        edit_structure(\n            \"/Game/Structs/PlayerData\",\n            {\"Score\": 0.0},\n            {\"type_hints\": {\"Score\": \"float\"}}  # was int, now float\n        )\n\n        # Remove a field\n        edit_structure(\n            \"/Game/Structs/PlayerData\",\n            {},\n            {\"remove_properties\": [\"ObsoleteField\"]}\n        )\n\n        # Rename a field\n        edit_structure(\n            \"/Game/Structs/PlayerData\",\n            {},\n            {\"renames\": {\"OldName\": \"NewName\"}}\n        )\n    ","inputSchema":{"type":"object","properties":{"soft_path":{"title":"Soft Path","type":"string"},"properties":{"type":"object","additionalProperties":true,"title":"Properties"},"properties_settings":{"additionalProperties":true,"title":"Properties Settings","type":"object"}},"required":["soft_path","properties","properties_settings"],"title":"edit_structureArguments"}},{"name":"add_or_replace_rows_in_data_table","description":"\n    Add or replace rows in a data table. ALWAYS call `query_unreal_project_assets` first to get the data table path, and content of the data table.\n\n    You must provide the soft path from the project root to the data table file.\n    Do not use a relative path, instead use a soft path.\n    e.g. don't use: Content/MyFolder/MyDataTable.uasset\n    use: /Game/MyFolder/MyDataTable\n\n    soft_path: The path to the data table file.\n    row_datas: The row name/data pairs to add to the data table as a dictionary. This will be automatically handled as JSON.\n    ","inputSchema":{"type":"object","properties":{"soft_path":{"title":"Soft Path","type":"string"},"row_datas":{"additionalProperties":{"additionalProperties":true,"type":"object"},"title":"Row Datas","type":"object"}},"required":["soft_path","row_datas"],"title":"add_or_replace_rows_in_data_tableArguments"}},{"name":"remove_rows_from_data_table","description":"\n    Remove a row from a data table.\n\n    You must provide the soft path from the project root to the data table file.\n    Do not use a relative path, instead use a soft path.\n    e.g. don't use: Content/MyFolder/MyDataTable.uasset\n    use: /Game/MyFolder/MyDataTable\n\n    soft_path: The path to the data table file.\n    row_name: The name of the row to remove.\n    ","inputSchema":{"type":"object","properties":{"soft_path":{"title":"Soft Path","type":"string"},"row_names":{"items":{"type":"string"},"title":"Row Names","type":"array"}},"required":["soft_path","row_names"],"title":"remove_rows_from_data_tableArguments"}},{"name":"get_data_asset_types","description":"\n    Get all data asset types in the project. Call this before calling `get_data_asset_type_info` to get a list of valid data asset types.\n    ","inputSchema":{"type":"object","properties":{"dummy_input":{"title":"Dummy Input","type":"string"}},"required":["dummy_input"],"title":"get_data_asset_typesArguments"}},{"name":"get_data_asset_type_info","description":"\n    Get detailed information about a specific data asset type, including its properties and inheritance. ALWAYS call `get_data_asset_types` first to get a list of valid data asset types, then call this before attempting to create a data asset.\n\n    This tool provides comprehensive information about a UDataAsset-derived class, including:\n    - Class name and full path\n    - Parent class information\n    - All properties with their types and Unreal Engine flags\n    - Additional type information for complex properties (Objects, Classes, Structs, Enums, Arrays)\n\n    Args:\n        data_asset_type: The name or path of the data asset class to inspect. Can be:\n            - Simple class name (e.g., \"MyDataAsset\")\n            - Class name with U prefix (e.g., \"UMyDataAsset\")\n            - Full class path (e.g., \"/Script/MyModule.MyDataAsset\")\n\n    Returns:\n        Detailed information about the data asset class including all its properties,\n        types, and Unreal Engine-specific metadata.\n\n    Examples:\n        # Get info about a custom data asset class\n        get_data_asset_type_info(\"MyCustomDataAsset\")\n\n        # Get info about an engine data asset class\n        get_data_asset_type_info(\"UPrimaryDataAsset\")\n\n        # Use full path if needed\n        get_data_asset_type_info(\"/Script/MyGame.MyDataAsset\")\n    ","inputSchema":{"type":"object","properties":{"data_asset_type":{"title":"Data Asset Type","type":"string"}},"required":["data_asset_type"],"title":"get_data_asset_type_infoArguments"}},{"name":"edit_widget","description":"Modify a UMG Widget Blueprint's widget tree by applying an ordered list of operations.\n\n    IMPORTANT: You MUST call fetch_ui_best_practices before using this tool.\n    The widget tree text format used by \"add\" operations is documented there.\n\n    Use get_asset_meta with parts=[\"WidgetTree\"] to inspect the current widget tree state.\n    \n    After making changes, use take_editor_screenshot with mode=\"viewport\" and the asset_path to visually\n    verify your work. When you do this, you SHOULD choose max_width/max_height values that roughly match\n    the size and aspect ratio you expect the widget to be used at in-game (for example, 512x288 for a \n    widescreen HUD, 400x400 for an inventory window, or 512x320 for a menu).\n\n    OPERATION SIZE GUIDELINES:\n    - You should only add or modify approximately 20 widgets per edit_widget call.\n    - For larger UI changes, break the work into MULTIPLE calls:\n        * First call: create the high-level container/layout structure (panels, key wrappers, major sections).\n        * Follow-up calls: fill in leaf widgets (buttons, text blocks, icons, etc.) and apply detailed styling.\n    - Do NOT try to build an entire complex screen or deeply nested tree in a single edit_widget invocation.\n\n    Parameters:\n    - asset_path: Soft path to the Widget Blueprint (e.g., \"/Game/UI/WBP_HUD\")\n    - operations: Ordered list of operation objects. Each has a \"type\" field.\n\n    ## \"add\" — add a widget subtree\n    {\"type\": \"add\", \"parent\": \"RootPanel\", \"widgetTree\": \"TextBlock \"Title\"\n  Text=\"Hello\"\"}\n\n    Omit \"parent\" to set the root widget on an empty tree. Use \"afterSibling\" to insert after a specific child.\n    The widgetTree field uses indentation-based text: ClassName \"Name\", children indented under parents,\n    slot properties in a Slot <Type>: block, widget properties as Key=Value lines.\n\n    ## \"remove\" — remove widgets by name (children removed recursively)\n    {\"type\": \"remove\", \"widgets\": [\"OldButton\", \"OldText\"]}\n\n    ## \"update\" — update properties/slot on an existing widget\n    {\"type\": \"update\", \"widget\": \"HealthBar\", \"properties\": {\"Percent\": \"0.5\"}, \"slot\": {\"Padding\": \"(Left=10,Top=5)\"}}\n\n    ## \"reparent\" — move an existing widget under a new parent (preserves subtree)\n    {\"type\": \"reparent\", \"widget\": \"HealthBar\", \"newParent\": \"Wrapper\"}\n\n    Use \"afterSibling\" to control insertion position under the new parent.\n\n    ## Wrap example (add wrapper, then reparent existing widget into it):\n    [\n      {\"type\": \"add\", \"parent\": \"RootCanvas\", \"widgetTree\": \"SizeBox \"Wrapper\"\"},\n      {\"type\": \"reparent\", \"widget\": \"HealthBar\", \"newParent\": \"Wrapper\"}\n    ]\n\n    ## Unwrap example (reparent children out, then remove the wrapper):\n    [\n      {\"type\": \"reparent\", \"widget\": \"HealthBar\", \"newParent\": \"RootCanvas\"},\n      {\"type\": \"remove\", \"widgets\": [\"OldWrapper\"]}\n    ]\n\n    Operations execute in the order given, so earlier operations can set up state for later ones.\n    ","inputSchema":{"type":"object","properties":{"asset_path":{"title":"Asset Path","type":"string"},"operations":{"items":{"additionalProperties":true,"type":"object"},"title":"Operations","type":"array"}},"required":["asset_path","operations"],"title":"edit_widgetArguments"}},{"name":"create_assets","description":"\n    Create a new assets in the project.\n\n    Args:\n        assets: List of asset definitions, each containing:\n            - soft_path: The path to the asset to create (e.g., \"/Game/Data/MyDataAsset\")\n            - asset_type: The type of asset to create (e.g., \"DataAsset\", \"Structure\", \"Enumeration\", \"Blueprint\")\n            - parent_class_name: The name of the parent class to create the new asset in (e.g., \"Actor\", \"Object\", \"Blueprint\"). Do not include the path to the parent class, just the name (except for Blueprints based on other Blueprint classes, where you should include the path to the parent blueprint class). For DataTable, this will set the row struct type (Format for DataTable is a soft path to the struct type)\n            - default_asset_data: Dictionary containing the new property values for the asset. For Blueprint, Actor Component, Object, Widget, Editor Utility Widget, this will add new properties to the blueprint. For DataAsset, this will set the default values for the data asset, make sure to call `get_data_asset_type_info` first to get the properties of the data asset type. For Structure, this will add properties to the structure. For Enumeration, this will add fields (Format for Enumeration is {\"EnumFields\": [\"Red\", \"Green\", \"Blue\", \"Yellow\"]}). For DataTable, this will populate the data table with default rows (The row name/data pairs to add to the data table as a dictionary).\n            - type_hints: Optional dictionary of type hints for complex properties\n\n    Valid asset types:\n    - DataAsset\n    - Structure\n    - Enumeration\n    - DataTable\n    - Blueprint\n    - Actor Component\n    - Widget\n    - Editor Utility Widget\n    - Object\n    - CurveFloat — standalone float curve asset (for timelines, animations, etc.)\n    - CurveVector — standalone vector curve asset (3 sub-curves: X/Y/Z)\n    - CurveLinearColor — standalone linear color curve asset (4 sub-curves: R/G/B/A)\n\n    Curve assets accept optional curve data in default_asset_data, structured to match UE's FRichCurve.\n    Omit default_asset_data to create an empty curve. Curve types do not use parent_class_name or type_hints.\n    To modify an existing curve asset, you should first call fetch_curve_best_practices and select the correct tool to modify it according to its instructions.\n\n    CurveFloat — JSON is a single FRichCurve at the top level:\n      {\n        \"is_event_curve\": false,               // optional, true marks this as an event curve (fires exec pins)\n        \"default_value\": 0.0,                  // optional, value when no keys\n        \"pre_extrap\": \"constant\",              // optional: constant|cycle|cycle_with_offset|oscillate|linear|none\n        \"post_extrap\": \"constant\",             // optional\n        \"keys\": [\n          {\n            \"time\": 0.0, \"value\": 0.0,\n            \"interp\": \"cubic\",                 // optional: cubic|linear|constant|none (default: cubic)\n            \"tangent_mode\": \"auto\",            // optional: auto|user|break|none (default: auto)\n            \"tangent_weight_mode\": \"none\",     // optional: none|arrive|leave|both\n            \"arrive_tangent\": 0.0,             // optional (for cubic + user/break tangent_mode)\n            \"leave_tangent\": 0.0,              // optional\n            \"arrive_tangent_weight\": 0.0,      // optional (for weighted tangent modes)\n            \"leave_tangent_weight\": 0.0        // optional\n          }\n        ]\n      }\n\n    CurveVector — each axis is an independent FRichCurve (can have different key counts/times):\n      {\n        \"x\": {\"keys\": [{\"time\": 0.0, \"value\": 0.0}, {\"time\": 2.0, \"value\": 100.0}]},\n        \"y\": {\"keys\": [{\"time\": 0.0, \"value\": 0.0}]},\n        \"z\": {\"keys\": [{\"time\": 0.0, \"value\": 0.0}, {\"time\": 2.0, \"value\": 500.0, \"interp\": \"linear\"}]}\n      }\n\n    CurveLinearColor — each channel is an independent FRichCurve:\n      {\n        \"r\": {\"keys\": [{\"time\": 0.0, \"value\": 1.0}, {\"time\": 1.0, \"value\": 0.0}]},\n        \"g\": {\"keys\": [{\"time\": 0.0, \"value\": 0.0}, {\"time\": 1.0, \"value\": 1.0}]},\n        \"b\": {\"keys\": [{\"time\": 0.0, \"value\": 0.0}]},\n        \"a\": {\"default_value\": 1.0, \"keys\": []}\n      }\n\n    NOTE: create_assets only creates NEW curve assets. To EDIT an existing curve's keyframes\n    (preserving the asset and all references to it), use fetch_curve_best_practices and call tools according to its instructions!\n\n    IMPORTANT!!! NO OTHER TYPES ARE SUPPORTED!!! Not materials, sounds, animations, or ANYTHING NOT included in the list above!!!\n    Do not use this tool to create interfaces. Prefer using the create_blueprint_interface tool instead.\n\n    Any property that takes instanced UObject type data (flagged as an EditInlineNew property specifier), needs to include a {\"_ClassName\": \"/Script/CodeModuleName.ClassName\"} mapping in the default_asset_data dictionary for any instance of that type of property.\n\n    Type Hints Format (same as create_data_asset):\n        Basic Types:\n        - \"bool\" or \"Boolean\"\n        - \"int\", \"int32\", or \"Integer\"\n        - \"float\" or \"Float\"\n        - \"double\" or \"Double\"\n        - \"string\", \"String\", or \"FString\"\n        - \"name\", \"Name\", or \"FName\"\n        - \"text\", \"Text\", or \"FText\"\n        - \"byte\", \"Byte\", or \"uint8\"\n        - \"int64\" or \"Int64\"\n\n        Common Unreal Structs (can use with or without F prefix):\n        - \"Vector\", \"FVector\", \"Vector2D\", \"FVector2D\", \"Vector4\", \"FVector4\"\n        - \"Rotator\", \"FRotator\", \"Transform\", \"FTransform\", \"Quat\", \"FQuat\"\n        - \"Color\", \"FColor\", \"LinearColor\", \"FLinearColor\"\n        - \"Guid\", \"FGuid\", \"DateTime\", \"FDateTime\", \"Timespan\", \"FTimespan\"\n        - \"IntVector\", \"FIntVector\", \"IntPoint\", \"FIntPoint\"\n\n        Any Unreal Engine Type (uses reflection system):\n        - Any UStruct name: \"GameplayTag\", \"GameplayAttribute\", etc.\n        - Any UClass name: \"StaticMesh\", \"Material\", \"Texture2D\", \"PlayerController\", etc. Don't include the U prefix, or a * prefix.\n        - Any UEnum name: \"ECollisionChannel\", \"EInputEvent\", etc.\n\n        Explicit Path References:\n        - \"struct:/Game/Path/To/MyStruct.MyStruct\"\n        - \"enum:/Game/Path/To/MyEnum.MyEnum\"\n        - \"class:/Game/Path/To/MyClass.MyClass\" (For blueprint classes, use the .MyClass_C suffix to get the generated class path)\n        - \"softclass:/Game/Path/To/MyClass.MyClass\"\n        - \"object:/Game/Path/To/MyClass.MyClass\"\n        - \"softobject:/Game/Path/To/MyClass.MyClass\" Only use this if asked by the user.\n\n        Container Types:\n        - \"array:ElementType\" - Array of ElementType (e.g., \"array:int\", \"array:Vector\", \"array:struct:/Game/MyStruct\")\n        - \"set:ElementType\" - Set of ElementType (e.g., \"set:string\", \"set:GameplayTag\")\n        - \"map:KeyType,ValueType\" - Map with KeyType keys and ValueType values (e.g., \"map:string,float\")\n        Map containers cannot contain other container types! To do nested containers, you must wrap those nested containers in a custom struct type.\n\n        Examples:\n        {\n            \"PlayerName\": \"string\",\n            \"Position\": \"Vector\",\n            \"Health\": \"float\",\n            \"PlayerType\": \"enum:/Game/Enums/EPlayerType\",\n            \"WeaponData\": \"struct:/Game/Structs/WeaponData\",\n            \"Inventory\": \"array:string\",\n            \"AbilityTags\": \"set:GameplayTag\",\n            \"Stats\": \"map:string,float\"\n        }\n\n    Returns:\n        JSON string containing the result of the asset creation operation\n\n    Examples:\n        # Single asset creation\n        create_asset(assets=[\n            {\n                \"soft_path\": \"/Game/Data/PlayerData\",\n                \"asset_type\": \"DataAsset\",\n                \"parent_class_name\": \"PrimaryDataAsset\",\n                \"default_asset_data\": {\"MaxHealth\": 100.0, \"Speed\": 500.0},\n                \"type_hints\": {\"MaxHealth\": \"float\", \"Speed\": \"float\"}\n            }\n        ])\n\n        # Batch asset creation\n        create_asset(assets=[\n            {\n                \"soft_path\": \"/Game/Data/PlayerInputMappingContext\",\n                \"asset_type\": \"DataAsset\",\n                \"parent_class_name\": \"InputMappingContext\",\n                \"default_asset_data\": {},\n                \"type_hints\": {}\n            },\n            {\n                \"soft_path\": \"/Game/Structs/WeaponData\",\n                \"asset_type\": \"Structure\",\n                \"default_asset_data\": {\"Damage\": 50.0, \"Range\": 1000.0},\n                \"type_hints\": {\"Damage\": \"float\", \"Range\": \"float\"}\n            },\n            {\n                \"soft_path\": \"/Game/Enums/WeaponType\",\n                \"asset_type\": \"Enumeration\",\n                \"parent_class_name\": \"\",\n                \"default_asset_data\": {\"EnumFields\": [\"Sword\", \"Bow\", \"Staff\"]},\n                \"type_hints\": {}\n            }\n        ])\n\n        # Curve asset creation\n        create_assets(assets=[\n            {\n                \"soft_path\": \"/Game/Curves/ElevatorAlpha\",\n                \"asset_type\": \"CurveFloat\",\n                \"default_asset_data\": {\n                    \"keys\": [\n                        {\"time\": 0.0, \"value\": 0.0},\n                        {\"time\": 3.0, \"value\": 1.0, \"interp\": \"cubic\"}\n                    ]\n                }\n            }\n        ])\n    ","inputSchema":{"type":"object","properties":{"assets":{"items":{"additionalProperties":true,"type":"object"},"title":"Assets","type":"array"}},"required":["assets"],"title":"create_assetsArguments"}},{"name":"edit_data_assets","description":"\n    Edit an existing UDataAsset-derived asset with new properties and values in the project. ALWAYS call `get_data_asset_types` first to get a list of valid data asset types, then `get_data_asset_type_info` to get the properties of the data asset type.\n\n    Args:\n        data_assets: List of data asset definitions, each containing:\n            - soft_path: The path to the existing data asset to edit (e.g., \"/Game/Data/MyDataAsset\")\n            - data_asset_type: The class type of the data asset being edited (e.g., \"PrimaryDataAsset\", \"MyCustomDataAsset\")\n            - default_data_asset_data: Dictionary containing the new property values for the data asset\n            - type_hints: Optional dictionary of type hints for complex properties\n\n    Any property that takes instanced UObject type data (flagged as an EditInlineNew property specifier), needs to include a {\"_ClassName\": \"/Script/CodeModuleName.ClassName\"} mapping in the default_asset_data dictionary for any instance of that type of property.\n\n    Type Hints Format (same as create_data_asset):\n        Basic Types:\n        - \"bool\" or \"Boolean\"\n        - \"int\", \"int32\", or \"Integer\"\n        - \"float\" or \"Float\"\n        - \"double\" or \"Double\"\n        - \"string\", \"String\", or \"FString\"\n        - \"name\", \"Name\", or \"FName\"\n        - \"text\", \"Text\", or \"FText\"\n        - \"byte\", \"Byte\", or \"uint8\"\n        - \"int64\" or \"Int64\"\n\n        Common Unreal Structs:\n        - \"Vector\", \"FVector\", \"Rotator\", \"FRotator\", \"Transform\", \"FTransform\"\n        - \"Color\", \"FColor\", \"LinearColor\", \"FLinearColor\"\n        - \"Guid\", \"FGuid\", \"DateTime\", \"FDateTime\", \"Timespan\", \"FTimespan\"\n\n        Explicit Path References:\n        - \"struct:/Game/Path/To/MyStruct.MyStruct\"\n        - \"enum:/Game/Path/To/MyEnum.MyEnum\"\n        - \"class:/Game/Path/To/MyClass.MyClass\"\n        - \"softclass:/Game/Path/To/MyClass.MyClass\"\n        - \"object:/Game/Path/To/MyClass.MyClass\"\n        - \"softobject:/Game/Path/To/MyClass.MyClass\"\n\n        Container Types:\n        - \"array:ElementType\" (e.g., \"array:float\", \"array:string\")\n        - \"set:ElementType\" (e.g., \"set:string\", \"set:GameplayTag\")\n        - \"map:KeyType,ValueType\" (e.g., \"map:string,float\")\n\n    Returns:\n        JSON string containing the result of the data asset editing operation\n\n    Examples:\n        # Edit an existing data asset with updated properties\n        edit_data_assets(\n            [\n                {\n                    \"soft_path\": \"/Game/Data/GameSettings\",\n                    \"data_asset_type\": \"PrimaryDataAsset\",\n                    \"default_data_asset_data\": {\n                        \"MaxHealth\": 150.0,\n                        \"MovementSpeed\": 600.0,\n                        \"PlayerName\": \"UpdatedPlayer\",\n                        \"NewProperty\": \"NewValue\"\n                    },\n                    \"type_hints\": {\n                        \"MaxHealth\": \"float\",\n                        \"MovementSpeed\": \"float\",\n                        \"PlayerName\": \"string\",\n                        \"NewProperty\": \"string\"\n                    }\n                }\n            ]\n        )\n\n        # Edit a data asset with complex properties\n        edit_data_assets(\n            [\n                {\n                    \"soft_path\": \"/Game/Data/WeaponData\",\n                    \"data_asset_type\": \"MyWeaponDataAsset\",\n                    \"default_data_asset_data\": {\n                        \"WeaponName\": \"Enhanced Sword\",\n                        \"Damage\": 75.0,\n                        \"WeaponType\": \"Magic\",\n                        \"DefaultLocation\": [50, 50, 50],\n                        \"AllowedUsers\": [\"Player\", \"NPC\", \"Boss\"],\n                        \"SpecialEffects\": [\"Fire\", \"Lightning\"]\n                    },\n                    \"type_hints\": {\n                        \"Damage\": \"float\",\n                        \"WeaponType\": \"enum:/Game/Enums/EWeaponType\",\n                        \"DefaultLocation\": \"Vector\",\n                        \"AllowedUsers\": \"array:string\",\n                        \"SpecialEffects\": \"array:string\"\n                    }\n                }\n            ]\n        )\n    ","inputSchema":{"type":"object","properties":{"data_assets":{"items":{"additionalProperties":true,"type":"object"},"title":"Data Assets","type":"array"}},"required":["data_assets"],"title":"edit_data_assetsArguments"}},{"name":"edit_blueprint","description":"\n    Edit a blueprint file.\n\n    You must provide the soft path from the project root to the blueprint file.\n    Do not use a relative path, instead use a soft path.\n    e.g. don't use: Content/MyFolder/MyBlueprint.uasset\n    use: /Game/MyFolder/MyBlueprint\n\n\n    - Don't use this tool (edit_blueprint) for creating events, that is handled by other graph editing tools.\n    - Don't plan on using delay nodes in functions, those can only be put in event graphs.\n    - If this tool returns errors, ALWAYS call get_asset_structs and retry 2 additional times before using a different method.\n\n    Args:\n        soft_path_from_project_root: The path to the blueprint file.\n        properties: A dictionary of properties to set.\n        properties_settings: A dictionary of metadata for the blueprint properties, including:\n            - add_properties_if_not_found: If True, add properties if they are not found. If False, only set properties that already exist.\n            - remove_excluded_properties: If True, remove all properties that are not specified in the properties dictionary. If False, keep all properties that are not specified in the properties dictionary.\n            - edit_existing_property_types: If True, the changes allow modifying existing properties.\n            - renames: A dictionary of property names to rename (key = old name, value = new name).\n            - type_hints: A dictionary of type hints for the structure. This is used to specify the type of each variable in the structure. Event dispatchers should be specified as \"EventDispatcher\".\n            - specifiers: A dictionary where keys are property names and values are dictionaries of specifier name -> value pairs.\n                Supported specifiers:\n                - \"ExposeOnSpawn\" (boolean): Makes the property available when spawning the Blueprint\n                - \"InstanceEditable\" (boolean): Controls whether the property can be edited on instances\n                - \"BlueprintReadOnly\" (boolean): Makes the property read-only in Blueprint graphs. Should remain false under most circumstances.\n                - \"Category\" (string): Sets the category for organizing properties in the editor\n                - \"Replication\" (string): Controls replication (\"None\", \"Replicated\", or \"RepNotify\")\n                - \"Tooltip\" (string): Sets the tooltip text for the property\n                - \"DisplayName\" (string): Sets a custom display name for the property\n        functions: List of function definitions. Don't use this tool (edit_blueprint) for creating events or RPC's, that is handled by graph editing tools. Each should contain:\n            - function_name: The name of the function to create or edit\n            - function_inputs: Optional dictionary of input parameter names and their types (e.g., {\"StartLocation\": \"Vector\", \"Speed\": \"float\"})\n            - function_outputs: Optional dictionary of output parameter names and their types (e.g., {\"Distance\": \"float\", \"IsValid\": \"bool\"})\n            - type_hints: Optional dictionary of explicit type hints for complex types\n        components: ONLY supported for ACTOR BLUEPRINTS. Actor components, Objects, Widgets, etc. are NOT supported. A list of components to add to the blueprint file. Each component is a dictionary with the following keys:\n            - component_type: The type of component to add. StaticMeshComponent, SkeletalMeshComponent, etc for default components. For custom components, use the soft path to the component class.\n            - component_name: The name to set the newly added component to.\n            - component_properties: A dictionary of properties to set on the component.\n            - component_type_hints: A dictionary of type hints for the component. This is used to specify the type of each variable in the component.\n            - is_new_component: Should a new component be created (True), or should an existing component be edited (False)?\n        interfaces: A list of interfaces to add to the implemented interfaces of the blueprint file. Each interface is a string of the soft path to the interface.\n\n\n        If no type hint is provided, the system will auto-detect the type from the JSON data.\n\n        Supported type hint formats:\n\n        Basic Types:\n        - \"bool\" or \"Boolean\"\n        - \"int\", \"int32\", or \"Integer\"\n        - \"float\" or \"Float\"\n        - \"double\" or \"Double\"\n        - \"string\", \"String\", or \"FString\"\n        - \"name\", \"Name\", or \"FName\"\n        - \"text\", \"Text\", or \"FText\"\n        - \"byte\", \"Byte\", or \"uint8\"\n        - \"int64\" or \"Int64\"\n\n        Common Unreal Structs (can use with or without F prefix):\n        - \"Vector\", \"FVector\", \"Vector2D\", \"FVector2D\", \"Vector4\", \"FVector4\"\n        - \"Rotator\", \"FRotator\", \"Transform\", \"FTransform\", \"Quat\", \"FQuat\"\n        - \"Color\", \"FColor\", \"LinearColor\", \"FLinearColor\"\n        - \"Guid\", \"FGuid\", \"DateTime\", \"FDateTime\", \"Timespan\", \"FTimespan\"\n        - \"IntVector\", \"FIntVector\", \"IntPoint\", \"FIntPoint\"\n\n        Common Unreal Objects:\n        - ParticleSystem\n        - SoundBase\n\n        Any Unreal Engine Type (uses reflection system):\n        - Any UStruct name: \"GameplayTag\", \"GameplayAttribute\", etc.\n        - Any UClass name: \"StaticMesh\", \"Material\", \"Texture2D\", \"PlayerController\", etc. Don't include the U prefix, or a * prefix.\n        - Any UEnum name: \"ECollisionChannel\", \"EInputEvent\", etc.\n\n        Explicit Path References:\n        - \"struct:/Game/Path/To/MyStruct.MyStruct\" User-defined struct\n        - \"enum:/Game/Path/To/MyEnum.MyEnum\"  User-defined enum\n        - \"class:/Game/Path/To/MyClass.MyClass\" (For blueprint classes, use the .MyClass_C suffix to get the generated class path)\n        - \"softclass:/Game/Path/To/MyClass.MyClass\"\n        - \"object:/Game/Path/To/MyClass.MyClass\"\n        - \"softobject:/Game/Path/To/MyClass.MyClass\"\n\n        Container Types:\n        - \"array:ElementType\" - Array of ElementType (e.g., \"array:int\", \"array:Vector\", \"array:struct:/Game/MyStruct\")\n        - \"set:ElementType\" - Set of ElementType (e.g., \"set:string\", \"set:GameplayTag\")\n        - \"map:KeyType,ValueType\" - Map with KeyType keys and ValueType values (e.g., \"map:string,float\")\n        Map containers cannot contain other container types! To do nested containers, you must wrap those nested containers in a custom struct type.\n\n        Examples:\n        {\n            \"PlayerName\": \"string\",\n            \"Position\": \"Vector\",\n            \"Health\": \"float\",\n            \"PlayerType\": \"enum:/Game/Enums/EPlayerType\",\n            \"WeaponData\": \"struct:/Game/Structs/WeaponData\",\n            \"Inventory\": \"array:string\",\n            \"AbilityTags\": \"set:GameplayTag\",\n            \"Stats\": \"map:string,float\"\n        }\n\n        <ReplicationReminders>\n           1. Do not use this tool to create RPC's, that is handled by graph editing tools.\n           2. You can use this tool to create OnRepNotify functions, these must be paired with replicated variables\n        </ReplicationReminders>\n\n    Reminders:\n    1. Any property that takes instanced UObject type data (flagged as an EditInlineNew property specifier), needs to include a {\"_ClassName\": \"/Script/CodeModuleName.ClassName\"} mapping in the default_asset_data dictionary for any instance of that type of property.\n\n    ","inputSchema":{"type":"object","properties":{"soft_path_from_project_root":{"title":"Soft Path From Project Root","type":"string"},"properties":{"type":"object","additionalProperties":true,"title":"Properties"},"properties_settings":{"additionalProperties":true,"default":null,"title":"Properties Settings","type":"object"},"functions":{"default":null,"items":{"additionalProperties":true,"type":"object"},"title":"Functions","type":"array"},"components":{"default":null,"items":{"additionalProperties":true,"type":"object"},"title":"Components","type":"array"},"interfaces":{"default":null,"items":{"type":"string"},"title":"Interfaces","type":"array"}},"required":["soft_path_from_project_root","properties"],"title":"edit_blueprintArguments"}},{"name":"create_blueprint_interface","description":"\n    Create a new Blueprint Interface in the Unreal Engine project.\n\n    Parameters:\n    - soft_path_from_project_root: The path where the Blueprint Interface should be created (e.g., \"/Game/Interfaces/MyInterface\")\n    - interface_functions: Optional list of function definitions to add to the interface. Each function should be a dict with:\n      - name: Function name (required)\n      - inputs: Optional dict of input parameter names to types\n      - outputs: Optional dict of output parameter names to types\n      - type_hints: Optional dict for additional type information\n\n    Example interface_functions:\n    [\n        {\n            \"name\": \"GetHealth\",\n            \"outputs\": {\"Health\": \"float\"}\n        },\n        {\n            \"name\": \"TakeDamage\",\n            \"inputs\": {\"DamageAmount\": \"float\", \"DamageType\": \"string\"},\n            \"outputs\": {\"WasKilled\": \"bool\"}\n        }\n    ]\n\n    Returns:\n    - Success message with the created interface path, or error message\n    ","inputSchema":{"type":"object","properties":{"soft_path_from_project_root":{"title":"Soft Path From Project Root","type":"string"},"interface_functions":{"anyOf":[{"items":{"additionalProperties":true,"type":"object"},"type":"array"},{"type":"null"}],"default":null,"title":"Interface Functions"}},"required":["soft_path_from_project_root"],"title":"create_blueprint_interfaceArguments"}},{"name":"compile_blueprint","description":"Compile a blueprint file.\n\n    Returns any errors or warnings that occurred during compilation.\n\n    You must provide the soft path from the project root to the blueprint file.\n    Do not use a relative path, instead use a soft path.\n    e.g. don't use: Content/MyFolder/MyBlueprint.uasset\n    use: /Game/MyFolder/MyBlueprint\n    ","inputSchema":{"type":"object","properties":{"soft_path_from_project_root":{"title":"Soft Path From Project Root","type":"string"}},"required":["soft_path_from_project_root"],"title":"compile_blueprintArguments"}},{"name":"spawn_blueprint_actors","description":"Spawn actors from a blueprint in the current level.\n\n    Args:\n        actors: A list of actors to spawn. Each actor is a dictionary with the following keys:\n            - actor_name: The name to give the spawned actor in the level.\n            - soft_path_from_project_root: The path to the blueprint file to spawn an actor from. Must be specified for each actor (can be different for each actor).\n                - Do not use a relative path, instead use a soft path. e.g. don't use: Content/MyFolder/MyBlueprint.uasset use: /Game/MyFolder/MyBlueprint\n            - location: Optional location where to spawn the actor. Format: [X, Y, Z]. Defaults to (0, 0, 0) if not provided.\n            - rotation: Optional rotation for the spawned actor. Format: [Pitch, Yaw, Roll]. Defaults to (0, 0, 0) if not provided.\n            - scale: Optional scale for the spawned actor. Format: [X, Y, Z]. Defaults to (1, 1, 1) if not provided.\n    Returns information about the spawned actors including their location and properties.\n    ","inputSchema":{"type":"object","properties":{"actors":{"items":{"additionalProperties":true,"type":"object"},"title":"Actors","type":"array"}},"required":["actors"],"title":"spawn_blueprint_actorsArguments"}},{"name":"get_blueprint_properties","description":"Get the properties of a blueprint file.\n\n    You must provide the soft path from the project root to the blueprint file.\n    Do not use a relative path, instead use a soft path.\n    e.g. don't use: Content/MyFolder/MyBlueprint.uasset\n    use: /Game/MyFolder/MyBlueprint\n    ","inputSchema":{"type":"object","properties":{"soft_path_from_project_root":{"title":"Soft Path From Project Root","type":"string"}},"required":["soft_path_from_project_root"],"title":"get_blueprint_propertiesArguments"}},{"name":"get_blueprint_component_properties","description":"Get the properties of a component in a blueprint file.\n\n    You must provide the soft path from the project root to the blueprint file.\n    Do not use a relative path, instead use a soft path.\n    e.g. don't use: Content/MyFolder/MyBlueprint.uasset\n    use: /Game/MyFolder/MyBlueprint\n\n    component_type: The type of component to get the properties of. StaticMeshComponent, SkeletalMeshComponent, etc for default components. For custom components, use the soft path to the component class.\n    component_name: The name of the component to get the properties of.\n    ","inputSchema":{"type":"object","properties":{"soft_path_from_project_root":{"title":"Soft Path From Project Root","type":"string"},"component_type":{"title":"Component Type","type":"string"},"component_name":{"title":"Component Name","type":"string"}},"required":["soft_path_from_project_root","component_type","component_name"],"title":"get_blueprint_component_propertiesArguments"}},{"name":"add_blueprint_node_to_strand","description":"\n    Add multiple nodes to a Blueprint's event graph using reflection.\n\n    This function can create multiple Blueprint nodes in a single operation by specifying a list of node configurations.\n    Each node in the list can be of any type and will be processed individually.\n\n    Args:\n        soft_path_from_project_root: Name/path of the Blueprint to modify\n        strand_name: Name of the strand to add the nodes to\n        nodes: List of node configuration objects, each containing:\n            - node_type: The K2Node class name (e.g., \"K2Node_Event\", \"K2Node_CallFunction\", \"K2Node_VariableGet\", \"K2Node_Self\", \"K2Node_InputAction\")\n            - node_position: Optional [X, Y] position for the node in the graph\n            - event_name: Required for K2Node_Event - name of the event (e.g., \"ReceiveBeginPlay\")\n            - function_name: REQUIRED for K2Node_CallFunction - name of the function to call (e.g., \"GetMesh\", \"SetMaterial\", \"PrintString\")\n            - target: REQUIRED for K2Node_CallFunction - the owning class of the function. ALWAYS provide this to ensure the correct function is resolved.\n              Common examples: \"Actor\" for GetActorLocation, \"UGameplayStatics\" for GetActorOfClass, \"UKismetSystemLibrary\" for PrintString,\n              \"UKismetMathLibrary\" for math functions, \"SkeletalMeshComponent\" for GetMesh on skeletal meshes, \"StaticMeshComponent\" for GetMesh on static meshes.\n              Without this, the wrong class's function may be used (e.g., GetMesh from StaticMeshComponent instead of SkeletalMeshComponent).\n            - component_name: Required for K2Node_VariableGet when accessing components\n            - variable_name: Required for K2Node_VariableGet when accessing variables\n            - action_name: Required for K2Node_InputAction - name of the input action\n            - params: Optional parameters to set on function call nodes\n            - node_properties: Optional properties to set on the node using reflection\n\n    Returns:\n        JSON string containing:\n        - strand_name: Name of the strand the nodes were added to\n        - total_nodes: Total number of nodes requested to be added\n        - successful_nodes: Number of nodes successfully added\n        - failed_nodes: Number of nodes that failed to be added\n        - successful: Array of successfully added nodes with their unique names and types\n        - failed: Array of failed nodes with error messages (only included if there are failures)\n\n    Examples:\n        # Create multiple nodes at once - note: target is REQUIRED for K2Node_CallFunction\n        add_blueprint_node_to_strand(\"/Game/MyBlueprint\", \"EventGraph\", [\n            {\n                \"node_type\": \"K2Node_Event\",\n                \"event_name\": \"ReceiveBeginPlay\",\n                \"node_position\": [100, 100]\n            },\n            {\n                \"node_type\": \"K2Node_CallFunction\",\n                \"function_name\": \"GetActorOfClass\",\n                \"target\": \"UGameplayStatics\",\n                \"params\": {\"ActorClass\": \"ACameraActor\"},\n                \"node_position\": [300, 100]\n            },\n            {\n                \"node_type\": \"K2Node_CallFunction\",\n                \"function_name\": \"GetMesh\",\n                \"target\": \"SkeletalMeshComponent\",\n                \"node_position\": [500, 200]\n            },\n            {\n                \"node_type\": \"K2Node_VariableGet\",\n                \"component_name\": \"StaticMeshComponent\",\n                \"node_position\": [500, 100]\n            },\n            {\n                \"node_type\": \"K2Node_VariableGet\",\n                \"variable_owner_class\": \"/Path/To/Class\",\n                \"variable_name\": \"MyVariable\",\n                \"node_position\": [500, 100]\n            }\n        ])\n\n        # Create a single node (still requires a list)\n        add_blueprint_node_to_strand(\"/Game/MyBlueprint\", \"EventGraph\", [\n            {\n                \"node_type\": \"K2Node_Self\",\n                \"node_position\": [200, 200]\n            }\n        ])\n    ","inputSchema":{"type":"object","properties":{"soft_path_from_project_root":{"title":"Soft Path From Project Root","type":"string"},"strand_name":{"title":"Strand Name","type":"string"},"nodes":{"items":{"additionalProperties":true,"type":"object"},"title":"Nodes","type":"array"}},"required":["soft_path_from_project_root","strand_name","nodes"],"title":"add_blueprint_node_to_strandArguments"}},{"name":"connect_blueprint_nodes","description":"\n    Connect multiple pairs of nodes in a Blueprint's event graph.\n\n    This tool allows you to connect multiple node pairs in a Blueprint's event graph in a single operation\n    by specifying a list of connection objects.\n\n    Args:\n        soft_path_from_project_root: The path to the Blueprint file (e.g., \"Game/MyBlueprint.uasset\")\n        strand_name: The name of the strand to connect the nodes in\n        connections: List of connection objects, each containing:\n            - source_node_unique_name: The unique name of the source node\n            - target_node_unique_name: The unique name of the target node\n            - source_pin: The pin on the source node to connect\n            - target_pin: The pin on the target node to connect\n\n    Returns:\n        JSON string containing:\n        - total_connections: Total number of connections attempted\n        - successful_connections: Number of successful connections\n        - failed_connections: Number of failed connections\n        - successful: Array of successful connection details\n        - failed: Array of failed connections with error messages (only included if there are failures)\n\n    Example:\n        connect_blueprint_nodes(\n            \"/Game/MyBlueprint\",\n            \"EventGraph\",\n            [\n                {\n                    \"source_node_unique_name\": \"node1_id\",\n                    \"target_node_unique_name\": \"node2_id\",\n                    \"source_pin\": \"exec\",\n                    \"target_pin\": \"exec\"\n                },\n                {\n                    \"source_node_unique_name\": \"node2_id\",\n                    \"target_node_unique_name\": \"node3_id\",\n                    \"source_pin\": \"output\",\n                    \"target_pin\": \"input\"\n                }\n            ]\n        )\n    ","inputSchema":{"type":"object","properties":{"soft_path_from_project_root":{"title":"Soft Path From Project Root","type":"string"},"strand_name":{"title":"Strand Name","type":"string"},"connections":{"items":{"additionalProperties":{"type":"string"},"type":"object"},"title":"Connections","type":"array"}},"required":["soft_path_from_project_root","strand_name","connections"],"title":"connect_blueprint_nodesArguments"}},{"name":"disconnect_blueprint_nodes","description":"\n    Disconnect multiple pairs of nodes in a Blueprint's event graph.\n\n    This tool allows you to disconnect multiple node pairs in a Blueprint's event graph in a single operation\n    by specifying a list of disconnection objects.\n\n    Args:\n        soft_path_from_project_root: The path to the Blueprint file (e.g., \"Game/MyBlueprint.uasset\")\n        strand_name: The name of the strand to disconnect the nodes in\n        disconnections: List of disconnection objects, each containing:\n            - source_node_unique_name: The unique name of the source node\n            - target_node_unique_name: The unique name of the target node\n            - source_pin: The pin on the source node to disconnect\n            - target_pin: The pin on the target node to disconnect\n\n    Returns:\n        JSON string containing:\n        - total_disconnections: Total number of disconnections attempted\n        - successful_disconnections: Number of successful disconnections\n        - failed_disconnections: Number of failed disconnections\n        - successful: Array of successful disconnection details\n        - failed: Array of failed disconnections with error messages (only included if there are failures)\n\n    Example:\n        disconnect_blueprint_nodes(\n            \"/Game/MyBlueprint\",\n            \"EventGraph\",\n            [\n                {\n                    \"source_node_unique_name\": \"node1_id\",\n                    \"target_node_unique_name\": \"node2_id\",\n                    \"source_pin\": \"exec\",\n                    \"target_pin\": \"exec\"\n                },\n                {\n                    \"source_node_unique_name\": \"node2_id\",\n                    \"target_node_unique_name\": \"node3_id\",\n                    \"source_pin\": \"output\",\n                    \"target_pin\": \"input\"\n                }\n            ]\n        )\n    ","inputSchema":{"type":"object","properties":{"soft_path_from_project_root":{"title":"Soft Path From Project Root","type":"string"},"strand_name":{"title":"Strand Name","type":"string"},"disconnections":{"items":{"additionalProperties":{"type":"string"},"type":"object"},"title":"Disconnections","type":"array"}},"required":["soft_path_from_project_root","strand_name","disconnections"],"title":"disconnect_blueprint_nodesArguments"}},{"name":"remove_blueprint_nodes","description":"\n    Remove multiple nodes from a Blueprint's graph.\n\n    This tool allows you to remove one or more nodes from a Blueprint's event graph by specifying their node IDs.\n    All connections to and from the removed nodes will be automatically severed.\n\n    Args:\n        soft_path_from_project_root: The path to the Blueprint file (e.g., \"Game/MyBlueprint.uasset\")\n        node_unique_names: List of node unique names to remove (e.g., [\"node-unique-name-1\", \"node-unique-name-2\"])\n        strand_name: The name of the strand to remove the nodes from\n        graph_type: The type of graph to remove the nodes from (Blueprint, Event, Function, or Macro)\n\n    Returns:\n        JSON string containing:\n        - removed_count: Number of nodes successfully removed\n        - requested_count: Number of nodes requested to be removed\n        - removed_node_unique_names: Array of node unique names that were successfully removed\n        - not_found_node_unique_names: Array of node unique names that were not found (if any)\n\n    Examples:\n        # Remove a single node\n        remove_blueprint_nodes(\"MyBlueprint\", [\"node-unique-name-1\"])\n\n        # Remove multiple nodes\n        remove_blueprint_nodes(\"MyBlueprint\", [\n            \"node-unique-name-1\",\n            \"node-unique-name-2\"\n        ])\n    ","inputSchema":{"type":"object","properties":{"soft_path_from_project_root":{"title":"Soft Path From Project Root","type":"string"},"strand_name":{"title":"Strand Name","type":"string"},"graph_type":{"title":"Graph Type","type":"string"},"node_unique_names":{"items":{"type":"string"},"title":"Node Unique Names","type":"array"}},"required":["soft_path_from_project_root","strand_name","graph_type","node_unique_names"],"title":"remove_blueprint_nodesArguments"}},{"name":"set_node_pins_defaults","description":"\n    Set default values for input pins on multiple Blueprint nodes.\n\n    This tool allows you to set default values for input pins on multiple nodes in a Blueprint's graph\n    in a single operation. Only input pins can have their default values set.\n\n    Args:\n        soft_path_from_project_root: The path to the Blueprint file (e.g., \"Game/MyBlueprint.uasset\")\n        strand_name: The name of the strand containing the nodes\n        nodes: List of node objects, each containing:\n            - node_unique_name: The unique name of the node to modify\n            - pin_defaults: Dictionary mapping pin names to their default values\n\n    Returns:\n        JSON string containing:\n        - total_nodes: Total number of nodes attempted to be processed\n        - successful_nodes: Number of nodes successfully processed\n        - failed_nodes: Number of nodes that failed to be processed\n        - total_pins_processed: Total number of pins attempted to be set across all nodes\n        - total_pins_successful: Total number of pins successfully set across all nodes\n        - total_pins_failed: Total number of pins that failed to be set across all nodes\n        - successful: Array of successfully processed nodes with their pin results\n        - failed: Array of failed nodes with error messages (only included if there are failures)\n\n    Examples:\n        # Set default values for multiple nodes\n        set_node_pins_defaults(\n            \"/Game/MyBlueprint\",\n            \"EventGraph\",\n            [\n                {\n                    \"node_unique_name\": \"function-node-123\",\n                    \"pin_defaults\": {\n                        \"X\": 10.0,\n                        \"Y\": 20.0,\n                        \"Message\": \"Hello World\",\n                        \"bEnabled\": True\n                    }\n                },\n                {\n                    \"node_unique_name\": \"move-node-456\",\n                    \"pin_defaults\": {\n                        \"Location\": [100.0, 200.0, 300.0],\n                        \"Speed\": 5.0\n                    }\n                }\n            ]\n        )\n\n        # Set default values for a single node (still requires a list)\n        set_node_pins_defaults(\n            \"/Game/MyBlueprint\",\n            \"EventGraph\",\n            [\n                {\n                    \"node_unique_name\": \"single-node-789\",\n                    \"pin_defaults\": {\n                        \"Value\": 42,\n                        \"Name\": \"Test\"\n                    }\n                }\n            ]\n        )\n    ","inputSchema":{"type":"object","properties":{"soft_path_from_project_root":{"title":"Soft Path From Project Root","type":"string"},"strand_name":{"title":"Strand Name","type":"string"},"nodes":{"items":{"additionalProperties":true,"type":"object"},"title":"Nodes","type":"array"}},"required":["soft_path_from_project_root","strand_name","nodes"],"title":"set_node_pins_defaultsArguments"}},{"name":"add_input_action_to_mapping_context","description":"\n    Add an Input Action to an Input Mapping Context for Enhanced Input System.\n\n    This tool adds a key mapping for an Input Action to an existing Input Mapping Context.\n    This is used with Unreal Engine's Enhanced Input System to create more flexible\n    and powerful input handling than the legacy input system.\n\n    Args:\n        mapping_context_path: Full path to the Input Mapping Context asset (e.g., \"/Game/Input/IMC_Default.IMC_Default\")\n        input_action_path: Full path to the Input Action asset (e.g., \"/Game/Input/IA_Move.IA_Move\")\n        key: Key to bind to the action (e.g., \"W\", \"A\", \"S\", \"D\", \"SpaceBar\", \"LeftMouseButton\", \"Gamepad_Left2D\")\n        negate: Whether to negate the input value (default: False)\n        swizzle_order: Axis swizzle order for multi-axis inputs (\"YXZ\", \"ZXY\", \"ZYX\", \"YZX\", \"XZY\", default: None)\n        scale: Scale modifier as a dictionary with x, y, z values (e.g., {\"x\": 1.0, \"y\": 1.0, \"z\": 1.0})\n\n    Returns:\n        JSON string containing the mapping details and success status\n\n    Examples:\n        # Add WASD movement keys to a mapping context\n        add_input_action_to_mapping_context(\n            \"/Game/Input/IMC_Default.IMC_Default\",\n            \"/Game/Input/IA_Move.IA_Move\",\n            \"W\",\n            swizzle_order=\"YXZ\"\n        )\n\n        add_input_action_to_mapping_context(\n            \"/Game/Input/IMC_Default.IMC_Default\",\n            \"/Game/Input/IA_Move.IA_Move\",\n            \"A\",\n            negate=True\n        )\n\n        add_input_action_to_mapping_context(\n            \"/Game/Input/IMC_Default.IMC_Default\",\n            \"/Game/Input/IA_Move.IA_Move\",\n            \"S\",\n            negate=True,\n            swizzle_order=\"YXZ\"\n        )\n\n        add_input_action_to_mapping_context(\n            \"/Game/Input/IMC_Default.IMC_Default\",\n            \"/Game/Input/IA_Move.IA_Move\",\n            \"D\"\n        )\n\n        # Add gamepad support\n        add_input_action_to_mapping_context(\n            \"/Game/Input/IMC_Default.IMC_Default\",\n            \"/Game/Input/IA_Move.IA_Move\",\n            \"Gamepad_Left2D\"\n        )\n\n        # Add jump action\n        add_input_action_to_mapping_context(\n            \"/Game/Input/IMC_Default.IMC_Default\",\n            \"/Game/Input/IA_Jump.IA_Jump\",\n            \"SpaceBar\"\n        )\n    ","inputSchema":{"type":"object","properties":{"mapping_context_path":{"title":"Mapping Context Path","type":"string"},"input_action_path":{"title":"Input Action Path","type":"string"},"key":{"title":"Key","type":"string"},"negate":{"default":false,"title":"Negate","type":"boolean"},"swizzle_order":{"default":null,"title":"Swizzle Order","type":"string"},"scale":{"additionalProperties":{"type":"number"},"default":null,"title":"Scale","type":"object"}},"required":["mapping_context_path","input_action_path","key"],"title":"add_input_action_to_mapping_contextArguments"}},{"name":"create_input_actions","description":"\n    Create a new InputAction asset for Enhanced Input System.\n\n    This tool creates a new InputAction asset that can be used with Input Mapping Contexts\n    to handle player input in Unreal Engine's Enhanced Input System.\n\n    Args:\n        input_actions: List of input actions to create, each containing:\n            - action_name: Name of the InputAction to create (e.g., \"IA_Jump\", \"IA_Move\", \"IA_Fire\")\n            - package_path: Content browser path where the InputAction should be created (default: \"/Game/Input\")\n            - value_type: Type of input value the action expects (default: \"Digital\")\n                - \"Digital\": Boolean input (pressed/not pressed) - for buttons, keys\n                - \"Axis1D\": Single float value - for triggers, scroll wheels\n                - \"Axis2D\": 2D vector input - for mouse movement, gamepad sticks\n                - \"Axis3D\": 3D vector input - for 3D motion controllers\n            - consume_input: Whether the action should consume input to prevent other systems from using it (optional)\n            - trigger_when_paused: Whether the action should trigger when the game is paused (optional)\n\n    Returns:\n        JSON string containing the created InputAction details including full path\n\n    Examples:\n        # Create a simple digital action for jumping\n        create_input_action([\n            {\n                \"action_name\": \"IA_Jump\",\n                \"package_path\": \"/Game/Input/Actions\"\n            }\n        ])\n\n        # Create a 2D axis action for movement\n        create_input_action(\n            [\n                {\n                    \"action_name\": \"IA_Move\",\n                    \"package_path\": \"/Game/Input/Actions\",\n                    \"value_type\": \"Axis2D\"\n                }\n            ]\n        )\n\n        # Create a 1D axis action for looking with specific settings\n        create_input_action(\n            [\n                {\n                    \"action_name\": \"IA_Look\",\n                    \"package_path\": \"/Game/Input/Actions\",\n                    \"value_type\": \"Axis2D\",\n                    \"consume_input\": True,\n                    \"trigger_when_paused\": False\n                }\n            ]\n        )\n\n        # Create an action that works when paused (for UI)\n        create_input_action(\n            [\n                {\n                    \"action_name\": \"IA_PauseMenu\",\n                    \"package_path\": \"/Game/Input/UI\",\n                    \"value_type\": \"Digital\",\n                    \"trigger_when_paused\": True\n                }\n            ]\n        )\n    ","inputSchema":{"type":"object","properties":{"input_actions":{"items":{"additionalProperties":true,"type":"object"},"title":"Input Actions","type":"array"}},"required":["input_actions"],"title":"create_input_actionsArguments"}},{"name":"create_gameplay_tag","description":"\n    Create new gameplay tags by adding them to an INI file.\n\n    This tool creates new gameplay tag entries in the specified INI file (defaults to DefaultGameplayTags.ini).\n    The tags will be added to the GameplayTagsSettings section and can be used throughout the project.\n\n    Args:\n        tag_names: List of gameplay tag names to create (e.g., [\"Ability.Jump\", \"Event.Character.Landed\"])\n                  Supports hierarchical tags using dot notation (e.g., \"Parent.Child.Grandchild\")\n        ini_file: Name of the INI file to write the tags to (default: \"DefaultGameplayTags.ini\")\n                 The file will be created in the project's Config directory if it doesn't exist.\n\n    Returns:\n        JSON string containing the created tag information including created tags, skipped tags (already existed), ini_file, and status\n\n    Examples:\n        # Create a single tag\n        create_gameplay_tag([\"Ability.Jump\"])\n\n        # Create multiple tags\n        create_gameplay_tag([\"Ability.Jump\", \"Ability.Dash\", \"Ability.Attack\"])\n\n        # Create tags in a custom INI file\n        create_gameplay_tag([\"Event.Character.Landed\", \"Event.Character.Jumped\"], \"CustomGameplayTags.ini\")\n\n        # Create hierarchical tags\n        create_gameplay_tag([\"Combat.Attack.Melee\", \"Combat.Attack.Ranged\"])\n    ","inputSchema":{"type":"object","properties":{"tag_names":{"items":{"type":"string"},"title":"Tag Names","type":"array"},"ini_file":{"default":"DefaultGameplayTags.ini","title":"Ini File","type":"string"}},"required":["tag_names"],"title":"create_gameplay_tagArguments"}},{"name":"fetch_blueprint_best_practices","description":"\n    Fetch the best practices for blueprint modifications. Call this before doing any blueprint modifications.\n    ","inputSchema":{"type":"object","properties":{},"title":"fetch_blueprint_best_practicesArguments"}},{"name":"fetch_audio_skill","description":"Fetch audio skill reference for MetaSound graph building, node API, templates, and sound design rules. skill_name must be 'metasound_knowledge'. Call this before generating any MetaSoundSource Python scripts in Augment, Edit, or Create-MetaSoundSource modes.","inputSchema":{"type":"object","properties":{"skill_name":{"title":"Skill Name","type":"string"}},"required":["skill_name"],"title":"fetch_audio_skillArguments"}},{"name":"fetch_material_best_practices","description":"Fetch material best practices and recipes for a specific category. Call this before creating complex or unfamiliar material types to get detailed guidance, parameter recipes, and workflow steps. category must be one of: landscape, water_vfx, pbr, effects, advanced, custom, general","inputSchema":{"type":"object","properties":{"category":{"title":"Category","type":"string"}},"required":["category"],"title":"fetch_material_best_practicesArguments"}},{"name":"fetch_niagara_best_practices","description":"Fetch the best practices for Niagara VFX creation and editing. Call this before doing any Niagara modifications.","inputSchema":{"type":"object","properties":{},"title":"fetch_niagara_best_practicesArguments"}},{"name":"fetch_niagara_skill","description":"Fetch a specialized Niagara VFX recipe for a specific effect type. Returns module compositions, material setup, and texture generation prompts. skill_name must be one of: fire_effect, smoke_effect, sparks_effect, rain_effect, snow_effect, magic_orb_effect, beam_effect, mesh_beam_effect, ribbon_trail_effect, explosion_effect, dust_debris_effect, water_splash_effect, impact_effect, trail_effect, ambient_loop_effect, energy_pillar_effect","inputSchema":{"type":"object","properties":{"skill_name":{"title":"Skill Name","type":"string"}},"required":["skill_name"],"title":"fetch_niagara_skillArguments"}},{"name":"lock_vfx_plan","description":"Validate and lock a VFX plan before building. Call with the full build_system plan (asset_path + emitters JSON). Returns validation results. Do NOT call build_system until this returns status='locked'.","inputSchema":{"type":"object","properties":{"asset_path":{"title":"Asset Path","type":"string"},"emitters":{"title":"Emitters","type":"string"}},"required":["asset_path","emitters"],"title":"lock_vfx_planArguments"}},{"name":"edit_mesh_postprocessing","description":"\n    Edit mesh post-processing properties for the currently selected actor in the Unreal Editor.\n    This tool allows you to modify mesh normals sharpness, commit scale to mesh geometry, set mesh pivot positions,\n    and remove generator metadata (Tripo task ID and generation parameters) from mesh assets.\n    You can perform multiple operations in a single call.\n\n    Args:\n        operations: List of mesh editing operations to perform. Options:\n            - \"set_sharp_angle\": Set the sharp edge angle threshold for mesh normals (0-180 degrees)\n            - \"commit_scale\": Commit the actor's current scale to mesh geometry and reset actor scale to (1,1,1)\n            - \"set_pivot\": Set the mesh pivot position (Center/Bottom/Target)\n            - \"remove_generator_metadata\": Remove generator metadata (task_id and generation parameters) from the mesh asset\n\n        angle: Sharp edge angle threshold in degrees (0-180). Only used with \"set_sharp_angle\" operation.\n               Lower values create sharper edges, higher values create smoother surfaces. Default: 180.0\n\n        pivot_position: Where to position the mesh pivot. Only used with \"set_pivot\" operation. Options:\n            - \"Center\": Center of the mesh bounding box\n            - \"Bottom\": Bottom center of the mesh bounding box\n            - \"Target\": Custom position (requires custom_position parameter)\n            Default: \"Center\"\n\n        custom_position: Custom pivot position as {\"x\": 0.0, \"y\": 0.0, \"z\": 0.0}.\n                        Only used with \"set_pivot\" operation when pivot_position is \"Target\".\n                        Default: None (uses {0, 0, 0} if needed)\n\n    Returns:\n        JSON string with the result of the mesh editing operations\n\n    Examples:\n        # Set sharp edge angle for normals only\n        edit_mesh_postprocessing([\"set_sharp_angle\"], angle=30.0)\n\n        # Commit scale to mesh geometry only\n        edit_mesh_postprocessing([\"commit_scale\"])\n\n        # Set pivot to bottom center only\n        edit_mesh_postprocessing([\"set_pivot\"], pivot_position=\"Bottom\")\n\n        # Remove generator metadata from selected mesh assets\n        edit_mesh_postprocessing([\"remove_generator_metadata\"])\n\n        # Multiple operations in one call\n        edit_mesh_postprocessing([\"set_sharp_angle\", \"set_pivot\"], angle=45.0, pivot_position=\"Bottom\")\n\n        # Set pivot to custom position\n        edit_mesh_postprocessing([\"set_pivot\"], pivot_position=\"Target\", custom_position={\"x\": 100.0, \"y\": 50.0, \"z\": 0.0})\n\n    Requirements:\n        - Must have one or more actors selected in the Unreal Editor viewport\n        - Selected actors must have valid StaticMeshComponents\n        - For pivot operations, the mesh assets must be writable (not in read-only packages)\n        - When multiple actors share the same mesh asset, modification happens once per unique asset\n        - Multi-actor operations use the last-selected actor as authority for shared assets\n    ","inputSchema":{"type":"object","properties":{"operations":{"items":{"type":"string"},"title":"Operations","type":"array"},"angle":{"default":180,"title":"Angle","type":"number"},"pivot_position":{"default":"Center","title":"Pivot Position","type":"string"},"custom_position":{"additionalProperties":{"type":"number"},"default":null,"title":"Custom Position","type":"object"}},"required":["operations"],"title":"edit_mesh_postprocessingArguments"}},{"name":"get_python_script_text","description":"\nOnly call this tool if you are the Python Agent.\nOnly call this tool at most once per Python Agent session. It is only applicable at the very beginning of the session to retrieve a past script by ID.\nRetrieve the full text of a previously cached Python script by its ID.\nThis is a companion tool to execute_unreal_python. Use this tool when you need to see the content of a script you previously generated or patched to inform future patches.\n    ","inputSchema":{"type":"object","properties":{"script_id":{"title":"Script Id","type":"string"}},"required":["script_id"],"title":"get_python_script_textArguments"}},{"name":"execute_unreal_python","description":"\nUsing best practices for Unreal Python, your task is to create a Python script based on a user's request, following Unreal Engine best practices and using the appropriate APIs for the specified Unreal Engine version.\nAlways only use this tool if another tool doesn't exist to perform the action you need. Example: don't use this tool to generate cpp files, use 'generate_cpp_file' or 'edit_cpp_file' instead.\n\n<IMPORTANT>You must follow this workflow in order:</IMPORTANT>\n\n0. Before your first execute_unreal_python call in a thread, call fetch_python_best_practices to load Unreal Python best practices and common pitfalls. Skip this step if you have already fetched them earlier in the conversation. (This step does not apply inside python_agent, which imports understandings individually.)\n1. Generate the Python script:\n   - Create a python_script_or_patch (string for new script, patch object { script_id: string, unified_diff_patch: string} for corrections to existing script) that fulfills the request_text\n   - Use only APIs that are appropriate and available for the specified unreal_version\n   - Follow the best practices from the relevant import_{category}_understanding tools\n   - Ensure the script is complete, functional, and properly handles errors\n   - #Important Logging Notes:# Keep printed output minimal, as you will be giving the user a more verbose summary using the results. No unnecessary formatting. No unnecessary debug logs. No progress logs. You should log warnings and errors where it will be useful for troubleshooting script failures. The user will not see the script output.\n2. Generate a short description:\n   - Create a short_description that summarizes what the overall script does\n   - Keep it to a single line with less than 128 characters\n   - Make it clear and suitable for display purposes\n   - This will be used for the UI to display in undo history if any assets are modified by the script\n   - You should reuse the short_description when patching if the resulting patched script is still doing the same thing\n3. On failure, attempt to correct the script via a patch. <IMPORTANT>The tool result will tell you if mandatory delegation to python_agent is required — you MUST follow those instructions exactly when they appear.</IMPORTANT>\n\n<YOLO_Mode:On>\n- Your tool call may be gated by a client-side approval UI\n- The user will see your generated script and description, then either Accept or Reject\n- If Accepted, the UI will execute your Script with ShortDescription\n- <IMPORTANT>If Rejected, ask the user for clarification or corrections and cease the task until the user gives you further instructions</IMPORTANT>\n</YOLO_Mode:On>\n<YOLO_Mode:Off>\n- Your tool call will be executed immediately\n</YOLO_Mode:Off>\n\n#Important interaction notes:#\n- The actual execution result will be posted back to you so you can see the output and respond accordingly\n- <IMPORTANT>PATCHING RULE: When retrying after a failure, you MUST use a patch object { script_id, unified_diff_patch } targeting the script_id from the failed attempt. NEVER regenerate the full script for a retry — always patch the existing one. Only use a full script string for completely new, unrelated tasks.</IMPORTANT>\n- Inside python_agent: You can use 'get_python_script_text' to retrieve the full content of a script by its 'script_id' if you need it for generating a patch.\n\nRemember: Your final output should contain only the results of execution. Do not include the scratchpad in your final output. Do not include the full python script code in your final output (it will already be shown to the user as a side-effect of the tool call).\n    ","inputSchema":{"type":"object","properties":{"python_script_or_patch":{"title":"Python Script Or Patch"},"request_text":{"default":"","title":"Request Text","type":"string"},"short_description":{"default":"","title":"Short Description","type":"string"}},"required":["python_script_or_patch"],"title":"execute_unreal_pythonArguments"}},{"name":"edit_timeline","description":"Create, configure, and modify Timelines on Unreal Engine actor blueprints.\n    \n    You may only use this via the bp_agent.\n    You must always call fetch_timeline_best_practices once before calling this tool. \n    \n    Args:\n        python_script: A Python script that follows the instructions from fetch_timeline_best_practices\n    ","inputSchema":{"type":"object","properties":{"python_script":{"title":"Python Script","type":"string"}},"required":["python_script"],"title":"edit_timelineArguments"}},{"name":"edit_eqs","description":"Create, configure, and modify EQS (Environment Query System) queries in Unreal Engine.\n\n    IMPORTANT: You MUST call 'fetch_eqs_best_practices' BEFORE using this tool.\n    The best practices contain the full API reference, available generators, tests,\n    property names, and usage examples you need to write correct scripts.\n\n    Write a Python script that runs in Unreal Engine's Python environment.\n    The `unreal` module is already available.\n\n    Args:\n        python_script: Python script for EQS query creation/modification.\n    ","inputSchema":{"type":"object","properties":{"python_script":{"title":"Python Script","type":"string"}},"required":["python_script"],"title":"edit_eqsArguments"}},{"name":"edit_curve","description":"Create, configure, and modify standalone Curve assets (CurveFloat, CurveVector, CurveLinearColor).\n\n    IMPORTANT: You MUST call 'fetch_curve_best_practices' BEFORE using this tool.\n    The best practices contain the full API reference for unreal.AuraCurveStatics,\n    JSON format documentation, and usage examples you need to write correct scripts.\n\n    Write a Python script that runs in Unreal Engine's Python environment.\n    The `unreal` module is already available.\n\n    Args:\n        python_script: A Python script that follows the instructions from fetch_curve_best_practices\n    ","inputSchema":{"type":"object","properties":{"python_script":{"title":"Python Script","type":"string"}},"required":["python_script"],"title":"edit_curveArguments"}},{"name":"generate_cpp_file","description":"\n    Generate a new Unreal Engine C++ class or source/header files in an existing code module with a consent-first flow.\n\n    Workflow and interaction rules:\n    - The client UI will present your proposed C++ files to the user for explicit Accept/Reject.\n    - By default, you must assume user consent is required; do not attempt to auto-apply changes.\n    - If the user Rejects, stop and ask clarifying questions before proceeding further.\n\n    What to produce:\n    - Provide the target file paths (header and/or source) relative to the project Source folder.\n    - Provide the full file contents for each file you intend to create.\n    - Ensure code compiles for the target Unreal version and follows UE coding standards.\n\n    Important guidance:\n    - Prefer minimal changes and clear, self-contained code.\n    - Include required UE includes and module exports as needed.\n    - If creating a UObject/Actor component, ensure correct macros, reflection specifiers, and constructors.\n    - Do not attempt to create new plugins or new code modules. If the user is trying to do this, give them information about how to do this instead of attempting to generate the files.\n\n    Args:\n        files: Array of files to create. Each entry must have 'path' (relative path under project, e.g., \"Source/MyGame/Public/MyActor.h\") and 'content' (full file content to write).\n        explanation: Optional short rationale describing the class/files to generate and their purpose.\n\n    Returns:\n        JSON string containing the result of the C++ file generation.\n    ","inputSchema":{"type":"object","properties":{"files":{"items":{"additionalProperties":{"type":"string"},"type":"object"},"title":"Files","type":"array"},"explanation":{"default":"","title":"Explanation","type":"string"}},"required":["files"],"title":"generate_cpp_fileArguments"}},{"name":"edit_cpp_file","description":"\n    Edit existing Unreal Engine C++ files with a consent-first flow.\n\n    Workflow and interaction rules:\n    - Before anything else, always use get_code_examples and/or grep to help find relevant files and code samples. This is mandatory.\n    - Before anything else, always use get_text_file_contents to gather additional information you need (especially as it relates to line numbers for patch hunk generation). This is mandatory.\n    - The client UI will preview your proposed edits for explicit user Accept/Reject.\n    - By default, assume user consent is required; do not auto-apply changes.\n    - If the user Rejects, stop and request clarification before proceeding further.\n\n    What to produce:\n    - Identify the target file and the exact edits to apply.\n    - Prefer apply_patch (git/unified-diff patches) that leverage line numbers and context; preserve formatting/style.\n    - Ensure resulting code compiles and follows UE coding standards.\n\n    Edit specification (discriminated union applied sequentially):\n    - { type: \"apply_patch\", patch: \"<unified diff for this file only>\" } - Preferred solution, most explicit and universally understood format\n    - { type: \"find_and_replace\", find: \"...\", replace: \"...\", index?: 0 } - Fallback for small, unambiguous changes\n    - { type: \"replace_content\", content: \"<entire file content>\" } - Replaces the whole file\n\n    Args:\n        path: Relative path to the file to edit (e.g., \"Source/MyGame/Private/MyActor.cpp\").\n        edits: Discriminated list of edits. Prefer type=\"apply_patch\" with a unified diff for precise changes; use type=\"find_and_replace\" as a fallback; use type=\"replace_content\" to rewrite the entire file.\n        explanation: Optional short rationale describing the change and expected behavior.\n\n    Returns:\n        JSON string containing the result of the C++ file edit.\n    ","inputSchema":{"type":"object","properties":{"path":{"title":"Path","type":"string"},"edits":{"items":{"additionalProperties":true,"type":"object"},"title":"Edits","type":"array"},"explanation":{"default":"","title":"Explanation","type":"string"}},"required":["path","edits"],"title":"edit_cpp_fileArguments"}},{"name":"create_text_file","description":"\n    Create new text files (.txt, .md, .csv, .xml, .json, .ini, .yaml, .yml, .toml, .cfg, .conf, .log, .py) with a consent-first flow.\n\n    **PLAN FILE RESTRICTION:**\n    - NEVER use this tool to create files in Saved/.Aura/plans/\n    - Plans must be created using the create_or_edit_plan tool in Plan Mode\n    - If user asks to create a plan, tell them: \"To create plans, please switch to Plan Mode using the mode selector.\"\n\n    Workflow and interaction rules:\n    - The client UI will present your proposed files to the user for explicit Accept/Reject.\n    - By default, assume user consent is required; do not attempt to auto-apply changes.\n    - If the user Rejects, stop and ask clarifying questions before proceeding further.\n\n    What to produce:\n    - Provide the target file paths relative to the project root.\n    - Provide the full file contents for each file you intend to create.\n\n    Allowed paths:\n    - Saved/.Aura/** (EXCEPT Saved/.Aura/plans/ - use Plan Mode for plans)\n    - Config/*.ini - For engine configuration files\n    - Content/Python/**.py - For python scripts\n\n    Examples:\n    - \"Saved/.Aura/notes/project_notes.md\" - A notes file\n    - \"Saved/.Aura/data/inventory.json\" - A data file\n    - \"Config/DefaultGame.ini\" - An engine config file\n    - \"Content/Python/my_python_script.py\" - A python script file\n\n    Args:\n        files: Array of files to create. Each entry must have 'path' (relative path under project, e.g., \"Saved/.Aura/notes/todo.md\") and 'content' (full file content to write).\n        explanation: Optional short rationale describing the files to create and their purpose.\n\n    Returns:\n        JSON string containing the result of the text file creation.\n    ","inputSchema":{"type":"object","properties":{"files":{"items":{"additionalProperties":{"type":"string"},"type":"object"},"title":"Files","type":"array"},"explanation":{"default":"","title":"Explanation","type":"string"}},"required":["files"],"title":"create_text_fileArguments"}},{"name":"edit_text_file","description":"\n    Edit existing text files (.txt, .md, .csv, .xml, .json, .ini, etc.) with a consent-first flow.\n\n    **PLAN FILE GUARDRAILS (Saved/.Aura/plans/):**\n    - You MAY mark steps complete (change \"- [ ]\" to \"- [x]\") during plan execution\n    - You must NOT restructure plans, add/remove steps, or change plan content\n    - For plan modifications: In Plan Mode, use the create_or_edit_plan tool. In other modes, tell the user: \"To edit this plan, please switch to Plan Mode using the mode selector.\"\n\n    Workflow and interaction rules:\n    - Before editing, use get_text_file_contents to read the file and gather line number information.\n    - The client UI will preview your proposed edits for explicit user Accept/Reject.\n    - By default, assume user consent is required; do not auto-apply changes.\n    - If the user Rejects, stop and request clarification before proceeding further.\n\n    What to produce:\n    - Identify the target file and the exact edits to apply.\n    - Prefer apply_patch (git/unified-diff patches) that leverage line numbers and context.\n    - Ensure the resulting file is valid and well-formed.\n\n    Edit specification (discriminated union applied sequentially):\n    - { type: \"apply_patch\", patch: \"<unified diff for this file only>\" } - Preferred for precise changes\n    - { type: \"find_and_replace\", find: \"...\", replace: \"...\", index?: 0 } - Fallback for small changes\n    - { type: \"replace_content\", content: \"<entire file content>\" } - Replaces the whole file\n\n    Allowed paths:\n    - Saved/.Aura/** - For plans, configs, and other Aura-managed files\n    - Config/*.ini - For engine configuration files\n\n    Args:\n        path: Relative path to the file to edit (e.g., \"Saved/.Aura/notes/todo.md\").\n        edits: Discriminated list of edits. Prefer type=\"apply_patch\" with a unified diff for precise changes.\n        explanation: Optional short rationale describing the change and expected behavior.\n\n    Returns:\n        JSON string containing the result of the text file edit.\n    ","inputSchema":{"type":"object","properties":{"path":{"title":"Path","type":"string"},"edits":{"items":{"additionalProperties":true,"type":"object"},"title":"Edits","type":"array"},"explanation":{"default":"","title":"Explanation","type":"string"}},"required":["path","edits"],"title":"edit_text_fileArguments"}},{"name":"trigger_live_coding","description":"\n    Trigger Live Coding compilation in Unreal Engine with a consent-first flow.\n\n    This tool triggers the Live Coding compile process in the running Unreal Editor instance.\n    Live Coding allows hot-reloading of C++ code changes without restarting the editor.\n\n    Workflow and interaction rules:\n    - The client UI will present the compile request to the user for explicit Accept/Reject.\n    - By default, you must assume user consent is required; do not attempt to auto-trigger.\n    - If the user Rejects, stop and ask clarifying questions before proceeding further.\n    - After triggering, the tool will wait for compilation results before returning.\n\n    What this tool does:\n    1. Calls UAuraCppStatics::TriggerLiveCodingCompile() in Unreal\n    2. Waits for the compilation to complete\n    3. Returns the compilation results (success/failure and any error messages)\n\n    Use this tool after making C++ file changes to compile and hot-reload them into the running editor.\n\n    Args:\n        explanation: Optional short explanation of why Live Coding is being triggered (e.g., \"Compiling changes to PlayerCharacter\").\n\n    Returns:\n        JSON string containing the compilation results.\n    ","inputSchema":{"type":"object","properties":{"explanation":{"default":"","title":"Explanation","type":"string"}},"title":"trigger_live_codingArguments"}},{"name":"search_unreal_python_api","description":"\nOnly call this tool if you are the Python Agent.\nSearch the Unreal Engine Python API documentation using semantic search.\n\nThis tool queries an embeddings database to find relevant Python API functions, classes, and methods\nbased on your search terms. It automatically uses the detected Unreal Engine version from the current project.\nThis tool supports multiple queries in a single call.\n\nUse this tool when you need to:\n- Find Python API functions for specific Unreal Engine functionality\n- Discover available methods on Unreal Python classes\n- Look up documentation for Unreal Python API usage\n\nThe tool returns a dictionary mapping each search term to its matching API entries, including function signatures and documentation.\n    ","inputSchema":{"type":"object","properties":{"search_terms":{"anyOf":[{"type":"string"},{"items":{"type":"string"},"type":"array"}],"title":"Search Terms"},"results_limit":{"default":3,"title":"Results Limit","type":"integer"}},"required":["search_terms"],"title":"search_unreal_python_apiArguments"}},{"name":"python_agent","description":"\n    This is the fallback you should delegate to for tasks that execute_unreal_python fails twice.\n    Create and execute Python scripts for Unreal Engine with access to Python API.\n    Important: Only call this tool when no other tools exist to perform the action you need.\n      - Prefer using edit_blueprint tool for property modifications on blueprints and their components (it is guaranteed to transact and is less error-prone than Python).\n    This agent automatically fetches best practices and searches the Python API before generating scripts.\n    Before calling this tool you must investigate the project using get_asset_meta, quicksearch, and query_unreal_project_assets and other tools and pass the data into relevant_data. \n    Filepaths, names, properties, types, components, and assets that are required for the python script to generate are important to include in JSON format. Each type of data should have it's own object.\n    Any context that is relevant to the thread must also be passed into previous_context in natural language, including previous errors for the same request if the first agent couldn't fix it.\n    The agent can also take an existing python_script_or_script_id in order to edit existing scripts or fix them.\n    \n    You are an expert Unreal Engine architect who's job is to write useful Unreal python dev tooling for users.\n    Create and execute Python scripts for Unreal Engine with access to Python API search and best practices.\n    \n    #Before calling this tool you must investigate the project using other tools and pass the data into relevant_data.#\n     - Use get_asset_meta to retrieve metadata about relevant assets\n     - Use query_unreal_project_assets to find specific classes, properties, and gameplay functionality defined in the project\n     - Use get_code_examples, grep, get_text_file_contents to find code related to specific classes, properties, and functions defined in C++\n     - Use other available tools to gather any additional context needed to fulfill the request\n     - Filepaths, names, properties, types, components, and assets that are required for the python script to generate are important to include in JSON format. Each type of data should have it's own object.\n     - Any context that is relevant to the thread must also be passed into previous_context in natural language, including previous errors for the same request if the first agent couldn't fix it.\n     \n     When reattempting a failed agent task, in which case you should use what you learned the last time as previous_context and relevant_data input to your next attempt, including the python_script_or_script_id of the relevant script to modify if available.\n    ","inputSchema":{"type":"object","properties":{"request_text":{"title":"Request Text","type":"string"},"relevant_data":{"anyOf":[{"additionalProperties":true,"type":"object"},{"type":"null"}],"default":null,"title":"Relevant Data"},"previous_context":{"anyOf":[{"type":"string"},{"type":"null"}],"default":null,"title":"Previous Context"},"short_description":{"anyOf":[{"type":"string"},{"type":"null"}],"default":null,"title":"Short Description"},"python_script_or_script_id":{"anyOf":[{"type":"string"},{"type":"null"}],"default":null,"title":"Python Script Or Script Id"}},"required":["request_text"],"title":"python_agentArguments"}},{"name":"bp_agent","description":"\n    Create and edit Unreal Engine blueprint graphs with automatic compilation checking.\n    This agent specializes in blueprint operations including creating, editing, and validating blueprint graphs.\n\n    Before calling this tool you must investigate the project using get_asset_meta, get_asset_graph, query_unreal_project_assets and other tools and pass the data into relevant_data.\n    Blueprint paths, graph information, components, properties, interfaces, and dependencies should be included in JSON format.\n    Any context relevant to the thread must also be passed into previous_context in natural language, including previous compilation errors if retrying.\n\n    This agent automatically fetches blueprint best practices and validates compilation after making changes.\n\n    Args:\n        request_text: The user's request or description of what blueprint changes should be made\n        relevant_data: JSON object containing blueprint data gathered from get_asset_meta, get_asset_graph, and other tools.\n            Should include:\n            - blueprint_paths: Soft paths to relevant blueprint files (e.g., '/Game/Blueprints/BP_MyActor')\n            - graph_info: Information about blueprint graphs to be edited (blueprint_path, graph_name, graph_type)\n            - components: Component information gathered from get_asset_meta\n            - properties: Blueprint properties gathered from get_asset_meta\n            - interfaces: Blueprint interfaces that need to be implemented\n            - dependencies: Other blueprints or assets this blueprint depends on\n        previous_context: Natural language context relevant to the thread, including previous errors or compilation failures if retrying\n        short_description: Short label/description for the blueprint task (for logs/UX), should be a single line less than 128 characters\n\n    Returns:\n        JSON string containing the results of blueprint operations, compilation results, and important context\n    ","inputSchema":{"type":"object","properties":{"request_text":{"title":"Request Text","type":"string"},"relevant_data":{"anyOf":[{"additionalProperties":true,"type":"object"},{"type":"null"}],"default":null,"title":"Relevant Data"},"previous_context":{"anyOf":[{"type":"string"},{"type":"null"}],"default":null,"title":"Previous Context"},"short_description":{"anyOf":[{"type":"string"},{"type":"null"}],"default":null,"title":"Short Description"}},"required":["request_text"],"title":"bp_agentArguments"}},{"name":"audio_agent","description":"\n    Create, edit, or augment audio assets in Unreal Engine using natural language.\n\n    Supports four modes:\n      - Generate: create a USoundWave from a text description via AI sound generation\n      - Augment: wrap an existing USoundWave in a MetaSoundSource with effects/looping/BP integration\n      - Edit: modify parameters on an existing MetaSoundSource asset\n      - Create-MetaSoundSource: build a procedural MetaSoundSource from scratch (oscillators, noise, envelopes)\n\n    For simple sound effects (\"make an explosion sound\"), this agent calls generate_audio\n    and returns the result in ~1 tool call. MetaSoundSource creation is only used when the\n    user explicitly requests effects processing, looping, parameter exposure, or Blueprint integration.\n\n    Before calling this tool, investigate the project using get_asset_meta, quicksearch, and\n    query_unreal_project_assets and pass the data into relevant_data.\n    For Edit or Augment modes, you MUST provide target_asset_path.\n\n    Args:\n        request_text: Natural language description of the sound to create/edit/augment\n        relevant_data: JSON object containing project data gathered from other tools.\n        previous_context: Natural language context from prior attempts, including errors.\n        short_description: Short label for logs/UX (single line, < 128 characters).\n        target_asset_path: Asset path for Edit/Augment modes (e.g. '/Game/Audio/MS_Explosion').\n    ","inputSchema":{"type":"object","properties":{"request_text":{"title":"Request Text","type":"string"},"relevant_data":{"anyOf":[{"additionalProperties":true,"type":"object"},{"type":"null"}],"default":null,"title":"Relevant Data"},"previous_context":{"anyOf":[{"type":"string"},{"type":"null"}],"default":null,"title":"Previous Context"},"short_description":{"anyOf":[{"type":"string"},{"type":"null"}],"default":null,"title":"Short Description"},"target_asset_path":{"anyOf":[{"type":"string"},{"type":"null"}],"default":null,"title":"Target Asset Path"}},"required":["request_text"],"title":"audio_agentArguments"}},{"name":"material_agent","description":"\n    Create and edit Unreal Engine materials via templates, custom graphs, instances, and texture inputs.\n    Handles all material operations including creating, editing, and applying materials.\n\n    Before calling this tool, gather relevant asset info using get_asset_meta and query_unreal_project_assets\n    and pass the data into relevant_data. Material paths, actor labels, and any known parameter values\n    should be included. Any context relevant to the thread must be passed into previous_context in\n    natural language, including previous errors if retrying.\n\n    This agent automatically determines save paths — do NOT specify a save directory for new materials.\n    Only pass paths of existing materials that need editing in relevant_data.material_paths.\n\n    Do NOT call python_agent or execute_unreal_python for material tasks — this agent handles all material operations.\n\n    Args:\n        request_text: The user's request describing what material changes should be made\n        relevant_data: Context gathered from get_asset_meta, query_unreal_project_assets, and other research tools.\n                       May include material_paths, actor_labels, parameters, and assets.\n        previous_context: Natural language context from the thread, including previous errors if retrying.\n        short_description: Short label for this material task (for logs/UX), single line under 128 characters.\n    ","inputSchema":{"type":"object","properties":{"request_text":{"title":"Request Text","type":"string"},"relevant_data":{"anyOf":[{"additionalProperties":true,"type":"object"},{"type":"null"}],"default":null,"title":"Relevant Data"},"previous_context":{"anyOf":[{"type":"string"},{"type":"null"}],"default":null,"title":"Previous Context"},"short_description":{"anyOf":[{"type":"string"},{"type":"null"}],"default":null,"title":"Short Description"}},"required":["request_text"],"title":"material_agentArguments"}},{"name":"behavior_tree_agent","description":"\n    Create and edit Unreal Engine Behavior Trees and Blackboard assets.\n    Use this instead of the Python Agent for Behavior Tree & Blackboard manipulation.\n\n    Before calling, gather BT asset paths and blackboard info using get_asset_meta, get_asset_graph,\n    and query_unreal_project_assets, then pass into relevant_data.\n\n    Use this agent for:\n    - Creating new Behavior Trees and Blackboard assets\n    - Getting available BT node classes\n    - Adding, removing, or modifying nodes in existing BTs\n    - Adding, removing, or modifying blackboard keys in existing BBs\n    - Inspecting BT/BB structures\n    - Any programmatic BT/BB construction or modification\n\n    Args:\n        request_text: The user's request or description of what the Behavior Tree should do\n        relevant_data: JSON object containing BT/BB data gathered from get_asset_meta, get_asset_graph, and other tools.\n            Should include:\n            - bt_paths: Soft paths to relevant Behavior Tree assets (e.g., '/Game/AI/BT_EnemyAI')\n            - blackboard_paths: Soft paths to Blackboard assets\n            - blackboard_keys: Known blackboard keys and their types\n            - asset_metadata: Additional asset metadata from get_asset_meta\n            - filepaths: Other relevant asset or file paths\n        previous_context: Natural language context relevant to the thread, including previous errors for the same request if the first agent couldn't fix it.\n        short_description: Short label/description for the task (for logs/UX), should be a single line less than 128 characters\n\n    Returns:\n        JSON string containing the results of BT/BB operations, script_id, and important context\n    ","inputSchema":{"type":"object","properties":{"request_text":{"title":"Request Text","type":"string"},"relevant_data":{"anyOf":[{"additionalProperties":true,"type":"object"},{"type":"null"}],"default":null,"title":"Relevant Data"},"previous_context":{"anyOf":[{"type":"string"},{"type":"null"}],"default":null,"title":"Previous Context"},"short_description":{"anyOf":[{"type":"string"},{"type":"null"}],"default":null,"title":"Short Description"}},"required":["request_text"],"title":"behavior_tree_agentArguments"}},{"name":"generate_audio","description":"\n    Generate a sound effect audio file from a text description using Aura's cloud sound generation service.\n    The generated audio is saved as a USoundWave asset in the project's Content directory.\n\n    This is the primary tool for creating sound effects. For simple sound generation, call this tool\n    and return the result — one tool call is all that's needed for most requests.\n\n    Only use MetaSoundSource creation (via execute_unreal_python) when the user explicitly requests\n    effects processing, looping, parameter exposure, or Blueprint integration.\n\n    IMPORTANT: If generation fails due to an API error, report it as a service error and suggest contacting Aura support.\n    Never mention the underlying API provider or suggest the user configure any API keys.\n    \n    Parameters:\n    - text: Natural language description of the sound to generate (max 1024 chars).\n      Be descriptive: \"heavy metal door slamming shut with reverb in a large hallway\" works better\n      than \"door slam\". Include material, environment, and character of the sound.\n    - sound_name: Desired filename for the asset (without extension). If empty, auto-derived from text.\n      Special characters are stripped, spaces become underscores.\n    - duration_seconds: Length of the generated audio in seconds (0.5 to 30.0, default 2.0).\n    - prompt_influence: How closely the output follows the text prompt (0.0 to 1.0, default 0.3).\n      Higher values = more literal interpretation, lower = more creative.\n    - cancellation_token: Optional token for cancelling the operation.\n\n    Returns:\n    - JSON with success status, asset_path (UE content path), full_path (disk path),\n      sound_name, and duration_seconds.\n    ","inputSchema":{"type":"object","properties":{"text":{"title":"Text","type":"string"},"sound_name":{"default":"","title":"Sound Name","type":"string"},"duration_seconds":{"default":2,"title":"Duration Seconds","type":"number"},"prompt_influence":{"default":0.3,"title":"Prompt Influence","type":"number"},"cancellation_token":{"anyOf":[{"type":"string"},{"type":"null"}],"default":null,"title":"Cancellation Token"}},"required":["text"],"title":"generate_audioArguments"}},{"name":"search_fab","description":"\n    Search the FAB marketplace (fab.com) for Unreal Engine assets.\n    Returns asset listings with thumbnails, prices, ratings, and FAB URLs.\n\n    Args:\n        query: Search keywords (e.g. \"medieval castle\", \"sci-fi weapon\", \"landscape material\")\n        price_filter: Price filter - \"all\" (default), \"free\", \"under_10\", \"under_25\", \"under_50\", \"under_100\"\n        category: Optional category filter - \"environments\", \"characters\", \"props\", \"materials\", \"vfx\", \"audio\", \"blueprints\", \"weapons\", \"vehicles\", \"animations\", \"ui\", \"hdris\", \"textures\", \"decals\"\n        sort_by: Sort order - \"relevancy\" (default), \"price_asc\", \"price_desc\", \"latest\", \"popular\"\n        max_results: Maximum number of results to return (1-20, default 10)\n\n    Returns:\n        JSON with FAB search results including thumbnails and pricing\n    ","inputSchema":{"type":"object","properties":{"query":{"title":"Query","type":"string"},"price_filter":{"default":"all","title":"Price Filter","type":"string"},"category":{"default":"","title":"Category","type":"string"},"sort_by":{"default":"relevancy","title":"Sort By","type":"string"},"max_results":{"default":10,"title":"Max Results","type":"integer"}},"required":["query"],"title":"search_fabArguments"}},{"name":"add_fab_asset_to_project","description":"\n    Open a FAB asset page in the user's default browser so they can add it to their Unreal Engine project.\n    The user can then use the \"Add to Project\" button on FAB to install it directly into their open UE project via the Fab plugin.\n\n    Args:\n        fab_url: The FAB URL of the asset (e.g., \"https://www.fab.com/listings/some-asset-slug\")\n        asset_name: Optional friendly name of the asset for display purposes\n\n    Returns:\n        JSON string with the result of opening the FAB asset page\n    ","inputSchema":{"type":"object","properties":{"fab_url":{"title":"Fab Url","type":"string"},"asset_name":{"default":"","title":"Asset Name","type":"string"}},"required":["fab_url"],"title":"add_fab_asset_to_projectArguments"}},{"name":"create_edit_material","description":"\n    Create and edit Unreal Engine materials via explicit operation dispatch.\n    This is the single MCP tool for all material operations. Claude orchestrates\n    multi-step flows with sequential calls (e.g. read_graph then edit_expressions).\n\n    Constraints:\n    - Default to Unlit unless PBR/realistic is explicitly requested.\n    - Saved/ texture paths in parameters or parameter_overrides are auto-imported into Content.\n    - Templates that accept texture_path: pbr_wood, pbr_stone, pbr_standard, pbr_metal,\n      pbr_plastic, panning_texture, toon_shading, force_field.\n    - Procedural templates (unlit_color, emissive_pulse, fresnel_glow, dissolve, hologram,\n      gradient, wireframe, glass) have no texture_path parameter.\n\n    Operations:\n\n        get_templates\n            Returns all 16 available templates with descriptions and parameters.\n            No extra params required. Call this first when unsure which template to use.\n\n        get_save_path\n            Returns the configured default save path for a material name.\n            Uses the user's MaterialGenerationSaveFolder setting (default: /Game/Generated_Materials).\n            Required: asset_path OR material_path (the material name, e.g. \"M_RustyMetal\")\n            Returns: {success, asset_path, save_folder}\n            Call this first when creating a new material to determine the correct save location.\n\n        create_from_template\n            Creates a material from a built-in template.\n            Required: asset_path, template_name\n            Optional: parameters (template-specific overrides; may include Saved/ texture paths\n                       which are auto-imported into Content before creation)\n            Templates — Unlit/effects: unlit_color, emissive_pulse, panning_texture,\n              fresnel_glow, dissolve, hologram, force_field, gradient, toon_shading, wireframe\n            Templates — PBR/lit: glass, pbr_standard, pbr_metal, pbr_wood, pbr_stone, pbr_plastic\n\n        create_empty\n            Creates a blank material as a starting point for custom graphs.\n            Required: asset_path\n            Optional: shading_model (default \"Unlit\"), blend_mode (default \"Opaque\"), two_sided (default False)\n\n        get_info\n            Returns metadata for a material: shading model, blend mode, parameter counts.\n            Required: material_path\n\n        read_graph\n            Returns a simplified JSON of a material's expression nodes, key property values,\n            and which output slot each node connects to. Call before edit_expressions.\n            Required: material_path\n\n        edit_expressions\n            Sets properties on expression nodes via UE reflection. Single recompile regardless of count.\n\n            Batch mode (preferred when editing >1 node — follows bpAgent pattern):\n              Required: material_path\n              Required: expression_edits — list of {expression_name: str, properties: {prop: value, ...}}\n              Example: expression_edits=[\n                  {\"expression_name\": \"ScanlinesParam\", \"properties\": {\"DefaultValue\": 5.0}},\n                  {\"expression_name\": \"FlickerSpeed\",   \"properties\": {\"DefaultValue\": 1.0}}\n              ]\n\n            Single mode (one node only):\n              Required: material_path, expression_name, expression_properties (dict of property->value)\n\n        create_instance\n            Creates a MaterialInstanceConstant from a parent material with parameter overrides.\n            Required: asset_path, parent_material_path\n            Optional: parameter_overrides {\"scalars\": {...}, \"vectors\": {...}, \"textures\": {...}}\n                       Saved/ texture paths in parameter_overrides are auto-imported before creation.\n\n        apply_to_actor\n            Applies a material to a mesh actor's slot(s) in the current level.\n            Required: actor_label, material_path\n            Optional: material_slot_index (default -1 = all slots)\n\n        add_texture_input\n            Adds a TextureSampleParameter2D to an EXISTING material and wires it to a\n            specified material output. Use this to add a normal map, roughness texture, etc.\n            to a material that was already created. Automatically configures sampler type\n            and texture compression for normal maps when target_input is \"Normal\".\n            Required: material_path, asset_path (texture package path, e.g. \"/Game/Textures/T_Normal\"),\n                      target_input (\"Normal\", \"BaseColor\", \"Roughness\", \"Metallic\", \"Specular\",\n                                    \"EmissiveColor\", \"Opacity\")\n            Optional: texture_parameter_name (default: derived from target_input, e.g. \"NormalMap\")\n            Saved/ texture paths in asset_path are auto-imported before use.\n\n        edit_instance\n            Edits parameter overrides on an EXISTING MaterialInstanceConstant.\n            Use list_parameters first to discover parameter names and current values.\n            Required: instance_path\n            Required: parameter_overrides {\"scalars\": {\"Name\": 1.0, ...},\n                                            \"vectors\": {\"Name\": [r,g,b,a], ...},\n                                            \"textures\": {\"Name\": \"/Game/Textures/T_Foo\", ...},\n            Saved/ texture paths in parameter_overrides are auto-imported before use.\n\n        list_parameters\n            Lists all exposed parameters and current values for a material or material instance.\n            For a base Material: returns parameter names and default values.\n            For a MaterialInstanceConstant: returns both parent defaults and current override values.\n            Call this before edit_instance to know which parameters exist.\n            Required: material_path (for a base Material) OR instance_path (for an MIC)\n\n        add_custom_expression\n            Adds a Custom (HLSL) expression node to an EXISTING material and optionally wires it\n            to a material output. Use this for advanced procedural effects that go beyond templates,\n            such as animated fire dissolves, custom noise patterns, ray-marching, and complex math.\n\n            The Custom node lets you write raw HLSL code. Define typed inputs so parameter nodes\n            or other expressions can feed data into the HLSL block.\n\n            Required: material_path, code (HLSL body)\n            Optional: output_type (\"float\", \"float2\", \"float3\", \"float4\" — default \"float3\")\n                      description (tooltip label in Material Editor)\n                      inputs — list of input specs. Each entry has:\n                               - \"name\" (required): pin name referenced in the HLSL code\n                               - \"type\" (optional): float/float2/float3/float4 — for code generation guidance\n                               - \"auto_connect\" (optional): inline-create and wire a helper source. Forms:\n                                   \"time\"                                      → Time node\n                                   \"texture_coordinate\"                        → TextureCoordinate (UV)\n                                   \"world_position\"                            → WorldPosition\n                                   {\"scalar_parameter\":{\"name\":\"Speed\",\"default\":1.0}}\n                                   {\"vector_parameter\":{\"name\":\"Color\",\"default\":[r,g,b,a]}}\n                                   {\"constant\":{\"value\":1.0}}\n                                   {\"expression\":\"MaterialExpressionXxx_0\"}    → wire to existing named node\n                      target_output — material pin to wire to: \"BaseColor\", \"Emissive\", \"Opacity\",\n                                      \"Normal\", \"Roughness\", \"Metallic\", \"Specular\", \"OpacityMask\",\n                                      \"WorldPositionOffset\", or \"\" for no auto-wire\n                      output_index — which output of the Custom node to wire (default 0)\n\n            IMPORTANT: If your HLSL references a named input (e.g. `return UV * Speed`), that input\n            MUST be wired to a real source — either via auto_connect (preferred, one call) or via a\n            separate add_expression + connect_expressions pair. Unwired inputs default to zero and\n            will produce wrong results (e.g. zero-speed animation).\n\n            Multiple Custom nodes can be added to the same material (e.g., one for BaseColor, one for Opacity).\n            After adding, use read_graph to see the node name, then edit_expressions to tweak Code or properties.\n\n        add_expression\n            Adds a standalone material expression node (ScalarParameter, VectorParameter,\n            TextureCoordinate, Time, Constant, Panner, Multiply, LinearInterpolate, etc.) to an\n            EXISTING material. Use this to create helper nodes that feed into Custom HLSL inputs\n            or to add user-tweakable parameters to a material built from create_empty.\n\n            Required: material_path, class_name (e.g. \"ScalarParameter\", \"TextureCoordinate\", \"Time\")\n            Optional: properties — dict of property -> value to set on the new node\n                                  (e.g. {\"ParameterName\":\"Speed\",\"DefaultValue\":1.0} for ScalarParameter)\n                      pos_x, pos_y — editor grid position (default -800, 0)\n\n            Prefer inline auto_connect in add_custom_expression when creating a helper purely to feed\n            an HLSL input — it's one call instead of two.\n\n            IMPORTANT: success=true means the node was created and saved. Property-setting failures\n            are reported in errors[] but do NOT flip success to false, because the node already\n            exists. If errors[] is non-empty, fix those properties with edit_expressions on the\n            returned expression_name — do NOT retry add_expression (that creates a duplicate node).\n\n        connect_expressions\n            Wires output pins of source expressions into input pins of target expressions.\n            Batch multiple connections in a single call (one recompile for the whole batch).\n\n            Required: material_path, connections — list of connection specs\n              Each spec: {\"from_expression\": \"Src_0\", \"from_output\": 0,\n                          \"to_expression\":   \"Dst_0\", \"to_input\":  \"Speed\"}\n              - to_input accepts an input pin NAME (string) or a stringified INDEX.\n                For Custom nodes, name matches the input declared via add_custom_expression.\n              - Set to_expression to the literal \"Material\" to wire into a material output pin\n                (to_input: BaseColor, Emissive, Opacity, Normal, Roughness, Metallic, Specular,\n                OpacityMask, WorldPositionOffset).\n\n    Returns:\n        JSON with operation results, asset paths, and relevant info\n    ","inputSchema":{"type":"object","properties":{"operation":{"title":"Operation","type":"string"},"asset_path":{"anyOf":[{"type":"string"},{"type":"null"}],"default":null,"title":"Asset Path"},"template_name":{"anyOf":[{"type":"string"},{"type":"null"}],"default":null,"title":"Template Name"},"parameters":{"anyOf":[{"additionalProperties":true,"type":"object"},{"type":"null"}],"default":null,"title":"Parameters"},"material_path":{"anyOf":[{"type":"string"},{"type":"null"}],"default":null,"title":"Material Path"},"shading_model":{"default":"Unlit","title":"Shading Model","type":"string"},"blend_mode":{"default":"Opaque","title":"Blend Mode","type":"string"},"two_sided":{"default":false,"title":"Two Sided","type":"boolean"},"parent_material_path":{"anyOf":[{"type":"string"},{"type":"null"}],"default":null,"title":"Parent Material Path"},"parameter_overrides":{"anyOf":[{"additionalProperties":true,"type":"object"},{"type":"null"}],"default":null,"title":"Parameter Overrides"},"actor_label":{"anyOf":[{"type":"string"},{"type":"null"}],"default":null,"title":"Actor Label"},"material_slot_index":{"default":-1,"title":"Material Slot Index","type":"integer"},"expression_name":{"anyOf":[{"type":"string"},{"type":"null"}],"default":null,"title":"Expression Name"},"expression_properties":{"anyOf":[{"additionalProperties":true,"type":"object"},{"type":"null"}],"default":null,"title":"Expression Properties"},"expression_edits":{"anyOf":[{"items":{"additionalProperties":true,"type":"object"},"type":"array"},{"type":"null"}],"default":null,"title":"Expression Edits"},"target_input":{"anyOf":[{"type":"string"},{"type":"null"}],"default":null,"title":"Target Input"},"texture_parameter_name":{"anyOf":[{"type":"string"},{"type":"null"}],"default":null,"title":"Texture Parameter Name"},"instance_path":{"anyOf":[{"type":"string"},{"type":"null"}],"default":null,"title":"Instance Path"},"code":{"anyOf":[{"type":"string"},{"type":"null"}],"default":null,"title":"Code"},"output_type":{"default":"float3","title":"Output Type","type":"string"},"description":{"anyOf":[{"type":"string"},{"type":"null"}],"default":null,"title":"Description"},"inputs":{"anyOf":[{"items":{"additionalProperties":true,"type":"object"},"type":"array"},{"type":"null"}],"default":null,"title":"Inputs"},"target_output":{"anyOf":[{"type":"string"},{"type":"null"}],"default":null,"title":"Target Output"},"output_index":{"default":0,"title":"Output Index","type":"integer"},"class_name":{"anyOf":[{"type":"string"},{"type":"null"}],"default":null,"title":"Class Name"},"properties":{"anyOf":[{"additionalProperties":true,"type":"object"},{"type":"null"}],"default":null,"title":"Properties"},"pos_x":{"default":-800,"title":"Pos X","type":"integer"},"pos_y":{"default":0,"title":"Pos Y","type":"integer"},"connections":{"anyOf":[{"items":{"additionalProperties":true,"type":"object"},"type":"array"},{"type":"null"}],"default":null,"title":"Connections"}},"required":["operation"],"title":"create_edit_materialArguments"}},{"name":"take_editor_screenshot","description":"Take a screenshot of an Unreal Editor window for visual verification.\n\n    Optionally positions the viewport camera before capturing, and restores\n    the original camera position afterwards so the user's view is not disrupted.\n\n    Args:\n        mode: What to capture:\n            - \"viewport\" — The visual preview of the asset or level. For Widget Blueprints this\n              captures the designer view. For levels (no asset_path) this captures the 3D viewport.\n              This is the most useful mode for verifying visual results.\n            - \"window\" — The entire editor window, including panels, toolbars, and details.\n            - \"pie\" — The Play-in-Editor game viewport (player camera). Requires PIE to be active.\n              Use this to capture what the player sees during gameplay testing.\n        asset_path: Optional. If provided, opens the asset's editor before capturing.\n            Works with any asset type: Widget Blueprints, Materials, Blueprints, levels, etc.\n            Example: \"/Game/UI/WBP_MainMenu\" or \"/Game/Materials/MI_Ground\"\n        max_width: Max width in pixels for the screenshot (default 512). Lower for faster/smaller images.\n        max_height: Max height in pixels for the screenshot (default 512). Lower for faster/smaller images.\n        camera_location: Optional. Position the camera before capturing. Dict with x, y, z keys.\n            Example: {\"x\": 100.0, \"y\": 200.0, \"z\": 300.0}\n            Only applies to \"viewport\" mode.\n        camera_rotation: Optional. Rotate the camera before capturing. Dict with pitch, yaw, roll keys.\n            Example: {\"pitch\": -30.0, \"yaw\": 45.0, \"roll\": 0.0}\n            Only applies to \"viewport\" mode. Requires camera_location to also be set.\n        restore_camera: If True (default), restores the camera to its original position after the\n            screenshot is taken. Set to False to leave the camera at the new position.\n    ","inputSchema":{"type":"object","properties":{"mode":{"default":"viewport","title":"Mode","type":"string"},"asset_path":{"default":"","title":"Asset Path","type":"string"},"max_width":{"default":512,"title":"Max Width","type":"integer"},"max_height":{"default":512,"title":"Max Height","type":"integer"},"camera_location":{"anyOf":[{"additionalProperties":true,"type":"object"},{"type":"null"}],"default":null,"title":"Camera Location"},"camera_rotation":{"anyOf":[{"additionalProperties":true,"type":"object"},{"type":"null"}],"default":null,"title":"Camera Rotation"},"restore_camera":{"default":true,"title":"Restore Camera","type":"boolean"}},"title":"take_editor_screenshotArguments"}},{"name":"start_pie","description":"Start a Play-in-Editor (PIE) session. The editor must have a level loaded.\n    Returns immediately — use is_pie_active to confirm the session has started.\n\n    Refuses if there are unsaved (dirty) packages so the PIE run reflects the\n    same asset state that was just edited. Save the listed packages first, or\n    pass force=True to start PIE anyway.","inputSchema":{"type":"object","properties":{"force":{"default":false,"title":"Force","type":"boolean"}},"title":"start_pieArguments"}},{"name":"stop_pie","description":"Stop the current PIE session.","inputSchema":{"type":"object","properties":{},"title":"stop_pieArguments"}},{"name":"is_pie_active","description":"Check whether a PIE session is currently running.\n    Returns is_active (bool) and time_seconds (float) if active.","inputSchema":{"type":"object","properties":{},"title":"is_pie_activeArguments"}},{"name":"simulate_left_stick","description":"Simulate left analog stick input (movement) in PIE.\n    direction_x: left/right (-1 to 1)\n    direction_y: forward/back (-1 to 1)\n    magnitude: stick deflection (0 to 1)\n    duration_seconds: how long to hold (0 = single frame)","inputSchema":{"type":"object","properties":{"direction_x":{"title":"Direction X","type":"number"},"direction_y":{"title":"Direction Y","type":"number"},"magnitude":{"default":1,"title":"Magnitude","type":"number"},"duration_seconds":{"default":0,"title":"Duration Seconds","type":"number"}},"required":["direction_x","direction_y"],"title":"simulate_left_stickArguments"}},{"name":"simulate_right_stick","description":"Simulate right analog stick input (camera) in PIE.\n    direction_x: camera yaw (-1 to 1)\n    direction_y: camera pitch (-1 to 1)\n    magnitude: stick deflection (0 to 1)","inputSchema":{"type":"object","properties":{"direction_x":{"title":"Direction X","type":"number"},"direction_y":{"title":"Direction Y","type":"number"},"magnitude":{"default":1,"title":"Magnitude","type":"number"}},"required":["direction_x","direction_y"],"title":"simulate_right_stickArguments"}},{"name":"simulate_button_press","description":"Simulate a button/action press in PIE.\n    action_name: Jump, Fire, Interact, Crouch, Sprint, or a direct key name\n    press_duration: how long to hold (0 = tap)","inputSchema":{"type":"object","properties":{"action_name":{"title":"Action Name","type":"string"},"press_duration":{"default":0,"title":"Press Duration","type":"number"}},"required":["action_name"],"title":"simulate_button_pressArguments"}},{"name":"simulate_key_press","description":"Simulate a raw key press in PIE.\n    key: Unreal key name (W, A, S, D, SpaceBar, LeftShift, etc.)\n    press_duration: how long to hold (0 = tap)","inputSchema":{"type":"object","properties":{"key":{"title":"Key","type":"string"},"press_duration":{"default":0,"title":"Press Duration","type":"number"}},"required":["key"],"title":"simulate_key_pressArguments"}},{"name":"inject_input_action","description":"Directly trigger an Enhanced Input Action by asset path, bypassing key bindings.\n    This is the most reliable way to trigger Enhanced Input actions in PIE.\n    action_path: full asset path (e.g. '/Game/G50/IA_g50_Push.IA_g50_Push')\n    value: for Boolean/Axis1D actions (default 1.0 = true/pressed)\n    x, y, z: for Axis2D/Axis3D actions","inputSchema":{"type":"object","properties":{"action_path":{"title":"Action Path","type":"string"},"value":{"default":1,"title":"Value","type":"number"},"x":{"default":0,"title":"X","type":"number"},"y":{"default":0,"title":"Y","type":"number"},"z":{"default":0,"title":"Z","type":"number"}},"required":["action_path"],"title":"inject_input_actionArguments"}},{"name":"get_input_mapping_context_keys","description":"Read an Input Mapping Context to see which keys are bound to which Input Actions.\n    context_path: full asset path (e.g. '/Game/G50/IMC_g50.IMC_g50')\n    Returns the list of key->action mappings with modifiers and triggers.","inputSchema":{"type":"object","properties":{"context_path":{"title":"Context Path","type":"string"}},"required":["context_path"],"title":"get_input_mapping_context_keysArguments"}},{"name":"get_player_transform","description":"Get the player pawn's transform in PIE (location, rotation, scale, velocity).","inputSchema":{"type":"object","properties":{},"title":"get_player_transformArguments"}},{"name":"set_player_transform","description":"Teleport the player pawn to a new location/rotation in PIE.\n    Only provided fields are changed; others stay the same.","inputSchema":{"type":"object","properties":{"x":{"default":null,"title":"X","type":"number"},"y":{"default":null,"title":"Y","type":"number"},"z":{"default":null,"title":"Z","type":"number"},"pitch":{"default":null,"title":"Pitch","type":"number"},"yaw":{"default":null,"title":"Yaw","type":"number"},"roll":{"default":null,"title":"Roll","type":"number"}},"title":"set_player_transformArguments"}},{"name":"get_actor_by_name_in_pie","description":"Find actors by name (partial match) in the PIE world.\n    Returns actor details including location, class, and properties.","inputSchema":{"type":"object","properties":{"name":{"title":"Name","type":"string"}},"required":["name"],"title":"get_actor_by_name_in_pieArguments"}},{"name":"wait_pie_seconds","description":"Wait for the specified number of seconds (max 30) in PIE. Blocks the MCP call.","inputSchema":{"type":"object","properties":{"seconds":{"title":"Seconds","type":"number"}},"required":["seconds"],"title":"wait_pie_secondsArguments"}},{"name":"wait_pie_frames","description":"Wait for the specified number of frames (max 600, ~10 seconds at 60fps) in PIE.","inputSchema":{"type":"object","properties":{"frames":{"title":"Frames","type":"integer"}},"required":["frames"],"title":"wait_pie_framesArguments"}},{"name":"get_screenshot_of_objects_for_verification","description":"Take a screenshot that frames all specified actors in view.\n    Positions the editor viewport camera to see all named actors with optimal framing,\n    then restores the camera to its original position so the user's view is not disrupted.\n    Uses a 30-degree elevation, 225-degree azimuth (3/4 view). Works in editor mode.\n\n    actors: list of actor name strings (partial match)\n    output_path: where to save the screenshot (absolute or relative to Saved/)\n    padding_percent: extra space around the bounding box (default 10%)","inputSchema":{"type":"object","properties":{"actors":{"items":{},"title":"Actors","type":"array"},"output_path":{"title":"Output Path","type":"string"},"padding_percent":{"default":10,"title":"Padding Percent","type":"number"}},"required":["actors","output_path"],"title":"get_screenshot_of_objects_for_verificationArguments"}},{"name":"create_easy_level_for_verification","description":"Create a clean, well-lit empty level for visual verification tests.\n    Includes a floor, directional light, sky light, and optional player start.\n    Cannot be called while PIE is active.\n\n    level_name: name for the level (default 'VerificationLevel')\n    floor_size: floor size in units (default 5000)\n    include_player_start: whether to add a PlayerStart (default True)","inputSchema":{"type":"object","properties":{"level_name":{"default":"VerificationLevel","title":"Level Name","type":"string"},"floor_size":{"default":5000,"title":"Floor Size","type":"number"},"include_player_start":{"default":true,"title":"Include Player Start","type":"boolean"}},"title":"create_easy_level_for_verificationArguments"}},{"name":"start_profiler_capture","description":"Start a performance profiler capture in Unreal Engine.\n\n    External MCP clients (Claude Code, Cursor, Junie, etc.) always run this\n    in autonomous mode — there is no React UI in your host to gate Start/Stop\n    on, so the call routes through the Aura MCP Bridge and the React\n    StartProfilerCaptureIntegratedTool runs with isMCPHeadless=true. The\n    IntegratedTool's existing autonomous-mode logic (5s default duration,\n    stop + poll for CSV writer finalization) handles the full flow and\n    returns capture results in this one tool call. This is analogous to how\n    execute_unreal_python auto-runs in YOLO mode for headless callers.\n\n    Args:\n        capture_type: \"csv\" (sustained, default) routes through the bridge.\n            \"stat_dump\" (one-shot frame averages) and \"gpu_profile\" (one-shot\n            GPU breakdown) call C++ directly — they have no UI gate and\n            return their full result immediately.\n        duration_seconds: For csv only. >0 = capture for N seconds. 0 = use\n            the IntegratedTool's headless default (5s).\n        autonomous: For csv only. Forwarded to the IntegratedTool as a hint;\n            isMCPHeadless=true already forces autonomous behavior on the\n            external-client path, so this flag is mostly cosmetic for\n            external callers. Kept in the schema for parity with the\n            frontend orchestrator's view of the same tool.\n\n    Returns:\n        JSON capture results from the IntegratedTool. For one-shot types,\n        the immediate dump from C++.\n    ","inputSchema":{"type":"object","properties":{"capture_type":{"default":"csv","title":"Capture Type","type":"string"},"duration_seconds":{"default":0,"title":"Duration Seconds","type":"integer"},"autonomous":{"default":false,"title":"Autonomous","type":"boolean"}},"title":"start_profiler_captureArguments"}},{"name":"stop_profiler_capture","description":"Stop an active CSV profiler capture and return the file path + frame count.\n\n    Internally: issues StopProfilerCapture (returns immediately with 'stopping'\n    while the CSV writer thread finalizes the file in the background) and then\n    polls PollProfilerStopResult every 500ms (up to 30s) until the writer's\n    OnCSVProfileFinished delegate fires. This mirrors the Live Coding compile\n    pattern — necessary because blocking the game thread on the delegate\n    deadlocks the writer's final flush.\n\n    Returns JSON: {\"status\":\"stopped\",\"file_path\":\"...\",\"frame_count\":N,...}\n    or {\"status\":\"error\",\"error\":\"...\"} if no capture is active or the writer\n    times out. After this returns, call analyze_profiler_capture for analysis.\n    ","inputSchema":{"type":"object","properties":{},"title":"stop_profiler_captureArguments"}},{"name":"analyze_profiler_capture","description":"Analyze a profiler capture file and return a JSON statistical summary.\n\n    Diagnostic workflow (DO NOT skip Step 2.5 when spikes exist):\n      1. CALL with category=\"summary\" first to get the verdict (CPU vs GPU bound).\n      2. Read `verdict` and `next_step` to determine which category to drill into.\n         CALL again with category=\"cpu\"/\"gpu\"/\"memory\"/etc. to see top_contributors.\n      2.5. ⚠ CRITICAL: top_contributors are CAPTURE-WIDE MEANS — they HIDE HITCHES.\n         If the response includes a non-empty `spikes` array (or frame_time.p99 is\n         meaningfully larger than frame_time.mean), call execute_unreal_python on\n         the file_path to load the CSV and find which columns were FAR above their\n         median on each spike frame index. Those are the actual hitch sources.\n         Without this step, hitch diagnoses based on averages will be WRONG.\n         The profiling_workflow skill has an example python pattern.\n      3. Call fetch_performance_best_practices for optimization guidance, citing\n         BOTH steady-state top contributors AND per-spike contributors.\n\n    Args:\n        file_path: Absolute path to the .csv file. Empty = use most recent capture.\n        category: \"summary\" | \"cpu\" | \"gpu\" | \"memory\" | \"draw_calls\" | \"threads\".\n            Always start with \"summary\" before drilling down.\n        top_n: Number of top contributors to include in breakdowns (default 10).\n\n    Returns:\n        JSON with verdict, frame_time/gpu_time/game_thread/render_thread stats,\n        budget analysis, top contributors ranked by mean time, and detected spikes.\n        The `next_step` field steers toward Step 2.5 (per-spike inspection) when\n        appropriate — read and follow it.\n    ","inputSchema":{"type":"object","properties":{"file_path":{"default":"","title":"File Path","type":"string"},"category":{"default":"summary","title":"Category","type":"string"},"top_n":{"default":10,"title":"Top N","type":"integer"}},"title":"analyze_profiler_captureArguments"}}]}]